1
00:00:01,305 --> 00:00:05,005
[music playing]

2
00:02:02,034 --> 00:02:08,954
[singing christmas carols]

3
00:02:08,998 --> 00:02:15,178
[laughter]

4
00:02:15,222 --> 00:02:17,702
Now, matron, we mustn't
keep Santa Claus waiting.

5
00:02:17,746 --> 00:02:18,703
Santa Claus!

6
00:02:18,747 --> 00:02:19,574
Santa Claus!

7
00:02:24,579 --> 00:02:28,887
[singing christmas carols]

8
00:02:31,412 --> 00:02:32,239
Merry Christmas.

9
00:02:35,285 --> 00:02:36,286
Oh, Countess!

10
00:02:36,330 --> 00:02:37,635
Merry Christmas, [inaudible].

11
00:02:37,679 --> 00:02:38,506
But Countess!

12
00:02:38,549 --> 00:02:39,811
Merry Christmas, doctor.

13
00:02:39,855 --> 00:02:41,857
You have no right to be here!

14
00:02:41,900 --> 00:02:43,293
You can't keep me out of this.

15
00:02:43,337 --> 00:02:45,034
But...

16
00:02:45,077 --> 00:02:47,428
Me, I've never been fond of
children's Christmas parties,

17
00:02:47,471 --> 00:02:48,951
- and I'm [inaudible].
- But...

18
00:02:48,994 --> 00:02:50,387
After all, this is much my
nursing home as it is yours.

19
00:02:50,431 --> 00:02:51,910
- But...
- Or hers.

20
00:02:51,954 --> 00:02:54,043
Well, nearly as much.

21
00:02:54,086 --> 00:02:55,610
Of course it is, but you have just

22
00:02:55,653 --> 00:02:56,698
had a very serious operation.

23
00:02:56,741 --> 00:02:58,221
Whose fault's that?

24
00:02:58,265 --> 00:03:00,658
It was you who kept on
about my grumbling appendix.

25
00:03:00,702 --> 00:03:01,920
Grumbling appendix, indeed.

26
00:03:01,964 --> 00:03:05,576
I believe you invented
the whole thing.

27
00:03:05,620 --> 00:03:09,232
[singing christmas carols]

28
00:03:09,276 --> 00:03:10,015
[inaudible]

29
00:03:10,059 --> 00:03:11,016
Happy Christmas.

30
00:03:11,060 --> 00:03:11,974
Happy Christmas, Jean.

31
00:03:12,017 --> 00:03:13,454
Happy Christmas, Francois.

32
00:03:13,497 --> 00:03:14,368
May we see mother?

33
00:03:14,411 --> 00:03:15,543
We'd like to show her the cake.

34
00:03:15,586 --> 00:03:17,022
Oh, I'm sure it'll be all right.

35
00:03:17,066 --> 00:03:18,763
Miss Cavell's not about.
She's not supposed to know this.

36
00:03:18,807 --> 00:03:19,808
Yes, I know, Jean.

37
00:03:19,851 --> 00:03:20,896
She's in the children's room.

38
00:03:20,939 --> 00:03:21,853
I'm sure it'll be great.

39
00:03:21,897 --> 00:03:22,593
Thanks.

40
00:03:28,295 --> 00:03:30,819
Matron, the Countess has called.

41
00:03:30,862 --> 00:03:32,212
Countess?

42
00:03:32,255 --> 00:03:33,517
Yes, she's with Dr. Depage
in your sitting room.

43
00:03:47,357 --> 00:03:49,272
[inaudible].

44
00:03:49,316 --> 00:03:53,450
[inaudible], the cake is here.

45
00:03:53,494 --> 00:03:54,886
Would you like to see it?

46
00:03:59,891 --> 00:04:01,328
Look.

47
00:04:01,371 --> 00:04:05,680
Jean made it all by
himself, didn't you, Jean?

48
00:04:05,723 --> 00:04:07,072
Good boy, Jean.

49
00:04:07,116 --> 00:04:08,944
[inaudible]

50
00:04:08,987 --> 00:04:11,076
I made the icing.

51
00:04:11,120 --> 00:04:13,427
Countess, what are you doing here?

52
00:04:13,470 --> 00:04:14,384
I'm walking.

53
00:04:14,428 --> 00:04:15,777
Merry Christmas.

54
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:17,561
I told her to rest,
but she's [inaudible].

55
00:04:17,605 --> 00:04:18,736
Oh, stuff and nonsense.

56
00:04:18,780 --> 00:04:19,824
Clear off.
Clear off.

57
00:04:19,868 --> 00:04:20,825
I don't need you.

58
00:04:20,869 --> 00:04:22,087
Who's is that?

59
00:04:22,131 --> 00:04:23,567
Madame [inaudible], Suzanne.

60
00:04:23,611 --> 00:04:25,090
She's quite a character.

61
00:04:25,134 --> 00:04:27,092
Do come here.

62
00:04:27,136 --> 00:04:28,485
Want to go to the Countess?

63
00:04:32,054 --> 00:04:33,925
Would you [inaudible]
come to Madame?

64
00:04:48,505 --> 00:04:51,856
Matron, could you come to the
small ward at once, please.

65
00:04:51,900 --> 00:04:53,815
I have to go and see
young Madame Rappard.

66
00:04:53,858 --> 00:04:54,816
She's very poor.

67
00:04:54,859 --> 00:04:55,730
I may need you doctor.

68
00:05:08,699 --> 00:05:11,180
The excitement...
the boys were here.

69
00:05:11,223 --> 00:05:13,182
They have a surprise for you.

70
00:05:13,225 --> 00:05:15,532
A cake for the children starving.

71
00:05:15,576 --> 00:05:19,362
And she wanted so much to see it.

72
00:05:19,406 --> 00:05:22,060
I'm not supposed to know.

73
00:05:22,104 --> 00:05:24,498
I understand.

74
00:05:24,541 --> 00:05:26,674
Don't spoil it for them.

75
00:05:26,717 --> 00:05:29,198
No, I won't.

76
00:05:29,241 --> 00:05:30,678
Merry Christmas, children.

77
00:05:30,721 --> 00:05:32,070
Merry Christmas, [inaudible].

78
00:05:35,683 --> 00:05:43,604
[cheering]

79
00:05:43,647 --> 00:05:45,606
Waiting for you.

80
00:05:45,649 --> 00:05:47,042
Please, go.

81
00:05:55,572 --> 00:05:57,008
[SOFTLY] Stay with her yourself.

82
00:05:57,052 --> 00:05:58,227
Send down if you need me.

83
00:05:58,270 --> 00:05:58,923
Yes.

84
00:06:12,502 --> 00:06:15,418
[children cheering]

85
00:06:15,462 --> 00:06:17,942
What a beautiful cake!

86
00:06:17,986 --> 00:06:19,422
This is you, I suppose.

87
00:06:19,466 --> 00:06:21,772
It was Madame Rappard's
idea, wasn't it, Jean.

88
00:06:21,816 --> 00:06:23,513
Yes, mother wanted to thank you.

89
00:06:23,557 --> 00:06:24,645
We all did.

90
00:06:24,688 --> 00:06:26,647
How very kind.

91
00:06:26,690 --> 00:06:28,126
Is it as good as it looks?

92
00:06:28,170 --> 00:06:30,128
Would you like to
try it, Miss Cavell?

93
00:06:30,172 --> 00:06:31,478
I think you better
cut it, Francois.

94
00:06:59,810 --> 00:07:03,640
[music playing]

95
00:07:17,349 --> 00:07:18,873
Oh.

96
00:07:18,916 --> 00:07:21,702
Your mother, rest her soul,
would be so proud of you.

97
00:07:21,745 --> 00:07:23,225
Thank you, grandmammy.

98
00:07:23,268 --> 00:07:24,922
Oh, goodbye, grandmammy.

99
00:07:24,966 --> 00:07:25,706
Don't worry.

100
00:07:25,749 --> 00:07:26,707
It'll soon be over.

101
00:07:26,750 --> 00:07:28,012
Goodbye, Francois.

102
00:07:28,056 --> 00:07:29,231
Be sure and take care
of grandma and the shop.

103
00:07:29,274 --> 00:07:30,232
Of course.

104
00:07:30,275 --> 00:07:31,233
Look, Jean.

105
00:07:31,276 --> 00:07:32,277
My first bake!

106
00:07:32,321 --> 00:07:35,498
Ah, it's as light as a feather!

107
00:07:35,542 --> 00:07:36,281
Don't worry, [inaudible].

108
00:07:36,325 --> 00:07:37,892
Keep [inaudible].

109
00:07:37,935 --> 00:07:41,809
[music playing]

110
00:07:54,909 --> 00:07:55,866
Goodbye, Jean.

111
00:07:55,910 --> 00:07:57,389
Be brave.

112
00:07:57,433 --> 00:07:59,391
Be brave!

113
00:07:59,435 --> 00:08:03,787
[music playing]

114
00:09:24,128 --> 00:09:26,087
[scream]

115
00:09:26,130 --> 00:09:27,784
Madame [inaudible]!

116
00:09:27,828 --> 00:09:30,613
Madame Countess, why don't we
go before we are all killed!

117
00:09:30,657 --> 00:09:32,267
Leave the Chateau?

118
00:09:32,310 --> 00:09:33,224
Certainly not.

119
00:09:33,268 --> 00:09:34,661
Nothing would induce me to.

120
00:09:34,704 --> 00:09:36,010
[bomb sound]

121
00:09:36,053 --> 00:09:38,055
Madame la Countess,
Madame la Countess!

122
00:09:38,099 --> 00:09:39,796
Stop making a noise
like a stuck pig.

123
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:41,145
Charlotte, pick up that bell.

124
00:09:41,189 --> 00:09:43,147
[FEARFULLY] All right,
Madame la Countess.

125
00:09:43,191 --> 00:09:44,453
Straighten the picture.

126
00:09:44,496 --> 00:09:46,107
You know how I hate
crooked pictures.

127
00:09:46,150 --> 00:09:47,412
But what is the use?

128
00:09:47,456 --> 00:09:49,153
In a few moments we
will be all dead!

129
00:09:49,197 --> 00:09:54,550
It would only be anticipating
the inevitable by a few years.

130
00:09:54,594 --> 00:09:57,031
[bomb sound]

131
00:09:57,074 --> 00:09:58,206
Albert...

132
00:09:58,249 --> 00:09:58,989
Yes.

133
00:09:59,033 --> 00:09:59,773
The picture.

134
00:09:59,816 --> 00:10:02,950
The picture.

135
00:10:02,993 --> 00:10:06,867
[music playing]

136
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:25,059
They're only a few miles off.

137
00:10:25,102 --> 00:10:26,103
[inaudible].

138
00:10:26,147 --> 00:10:27,496
Did you hear what [inaudible]?

139
00:10:27,539 --> 00:10:29,193
Burning the village
and killing the wounded!

140
00:10:29,237 --> 00:10:30,107
[loud] They are [inaudible]!

141
00:10:33,197 --> 00:10:37,027
[music playing]

142
00:11:03,924 --> 00:11:05,839
Your poor mother, rest her soul,

143
00:11:05,882 --> 00:11:08,058
would rather you'd been
born blind than to have

144
00:11:08,102 --> 00:11:09,973
you look on such a sight.

145
00:11:10,017 --> 00:11:14,412
[music playing]

146
00:11:28,905 --> 00:11:32,779
[soft music playing]

147
00:11:42,789 --> 00:11:43,790
Good evening, Madame Rappard.

148
00:11:43,833 --> 00:11:46,314
Matron, I am glad to see you.

149
00:11:46,357 --> 00:11:48,751
I'm so worried about Jean.

150
00:11:48,795 --> 00:11:50,013
Why, what's happened?

151
00:11:50,057 --> 00:11:52,624
They said he's been
captured by the Germans.

152
00:11:52,668 --> 00:11:54,670
Madame Rappard, you musn't
believe all you hear.

153
00:11:54,714 --> 00:11:56,541
Brussels is so full of rumors.

154
00:11:56,585 --> 00:11:58,326
Yes, but they say they're
shooting all the prisoners.

155
00:12:02,809 --> 00:12:05,072
[inaudible]

156
00:12:05,115 --> 00:12:07,291
Jean!

157
00:12:07,335 --> 00:12:08,292
Oh, Jean!

158
00:12:08,336 --> 00:12:11,208
[inaudible]

159
00:12:11,252 --> 00:12:14,734
[inaudible], my boy.

160
00:12:14,777 --> 00:12:18,085
I was captured, but I escaped.

161
00:12:18,128 --> 00:12:21,088
They saw me in the square
and they're after me!

162
00:12:21,131 --> 00:12:21,871
Don't let them catch me!

163
00:12:21,915 --> 00:12:22,654
No!

164
00:12:27,964 --> 00:12:28,617
Atten hut!

165
00:12:37,582 --> 00:12:40,150
Madame Rappard.

166
00:12:40,194 --> 00:12:43,153
[german word] hut!

167
00:12:43,197 --> 00:12:44,154
Quick!

168
00:12:44,198 --> 00:12:44,851
Quickly.

169
00:12:59,430 --> 00:13:00,823
Oh.

170
00:13:00,867 --> 00:13:01,519
Oh.

171
00:13:19,886 --> 00:13:20,800
[inaudible].

172
00:13:20,843 --> 00:13:22,671
[speaking in german].

173
00:13:22,714 --> 00:13:23,977
Ah, English.

174
00:13:24,020 --> 00:13:25,326
I am.

175
00:13:25,369 --> 00:13:26,370
Who lives here?

176
00:13:26,414 --> 00:13:27,632
This lady.

177
00:13:27,676 --> 00:13:30,374
As you see, she is not very well.

178
00:13:30,418 --> 00:13:32,724
Are there any
questions I can answer?

179
00:13:32,768 --> 00:13:33,856
We are building troops.

180
00:13:33,900 --> 00:13:37,207
How many she take here?

181
00:13:37,251 --> 00:13:37,817
Four.

182
00:13:51,265 --> 00:13:53,223
Jean.

183
00:13:53,267 --> 00:13:55,095
They are building
soldiers in the house.

184
00:13:55,138 --> 00:13:56,096
Keep very quiet.

185
00:13:56,139 --> 00:13:56,836
[speaking german].

186
00:14:02,058 --> 00:14:04,017
Madame Rappard.

187
00:14:04,060 --> 00:14:05,975
Madame Rappard.

188
00:14:06,019 --> 00:14:06,671
[speaking german]

189
00:14:11,676 --> 00:14:13,374
Where [inaudible]?

190
00:14:13,417 --> 00:14:15,332
You have to be very brave.

191
00:14:15,376 --> 00:14:17,073
They're building
soldiers in the house.

192
00:14:17,117 --> 00:14:18,161
Oh, what are we going to do?

193
00:14:18,205 --> 00:14:19,728
What are we going to do?

194
00:14:19,771 --> 00:14:20,947
Now, don't worry.

195
00:14:20,990 --> 00:14:22,339
But they'll be sure to find him.

196
00:14:28,258 --> 00:14:30,130
Keep him hidden until after curfew.

197
00:14:30,173 --> 00:14:32,219
Get some of his old
things together,

198
00:14:32,262 --> 00:14:34,395
and I'll come back and take
him to my nursing home.

199
00:14:34,438 --> 00:14:35,178
Oh!

200
00:14:35,222 --> 00:14:39,139
Oh, God bless you!

201
00:14:39,182 --> 00:14:42,533
[bell ringing]

202
00:14:58,462 --> 00:15:00,812
[dog barking]

203
00:15:10,344 --> 00:15:14,000
Fraulein, do you know
it is past curfew?

204
00:15:14,043 --> 00:15:15,001
I do.

205
00:15:15,044 --> 00:15:16,654
You should be in your house.

206
00:15:16,698 --> 00:15:18,700
I'm on my way to
a very urgent case.

207
00:15:28,231 --> 00:15:31,582
[bell ring]

208
00:15:50,036 --> 00:15:51,994
We might be able to get him away.

209
00:15:52,038 --> 00:15:56,564
One of the soldiers is
asleep in there by the stove.

210
00:15:56,607 --> 00:15:58,392
We must try.

211
00:15:58,435 --> 00:15:59,741
Is everything ready?

212
00:15:59,784 --> 00:16:01,090
Yes, he's got his
clothes in there with him.

213
00:16:01,134 --> 00:16:02,004
Come along then.

214
00:16:58,234 --> 00:17:00,106
[loud noise]

215
00:17:12,857 --> 00:17:13,510
Oh.

216
00:17:19,603 --> 00:17:20,952
What happened?

217
00:17:20,996 --> 00:17:24,347
Oh, I've taken every
bit of skin off my knee.

218
00:17:24,391 --> 00:17:27,829
That's what comes of having
a horde of men in the house.

219
00:17:27,872 --> 00:17:29,309
Oh.

220
00:17:29,352 --> 00:17:30,310
Oh.

221
00:17:30,353 --> 00:17:33,748
[music playing]

222
00:18:08,261 --> 00:18:09,871
Reported numerous escapes.

223
00:18:09,914 --> 00:18:13,004
Prisoners of war
from temporary camps.

224
00:18:13,048 --> 00:18:15,442
Probably seeking
refuge in Brussels.

225
00:18:15,485 --> 00:18:18,445
Immediate action demanded.

226
00:18:18,488 --> 00:18:21,187
Captain, you will take the
necessary steps to apprehend

227
00:18:21,230 --> 00:18:24,581
any refugee soldiers and
advise the civil population of

228
00:18:24,625 --> 00:18:25,974
the penalty for harboring them.

229
00:18:26,017 --> 00:18:27,018
[inaudible]

230
00:18:27,062 --> 00:18:28,759
What is it?

231
00:18:28,803 --> 00:18:30,152
Search all houses.

232
00:18:30,196 --> 00:18:32,502
And if you find anyone
looking suspicious,

233
00:18:32,546 --> 00:18:34,678
arrest him, and report
immediately to your sergeant.

234
00:18:43,774 --> 00:18:45,776
I'm one of the lucky ones.

235
00:18:45,820 --> 00:18:47,126
If you can see some of the others

236
00:18:47,169 --> 00:18:49,693
lying wounded in
trenches and shell holes.

237
00:18:49,737 --> 00:18:52,479
If you can only do something
for them like you did for me.

238
00:18:52,522 --> 00:18:54,437
We have to think of you now, Jean.

239
00:18:54,481 --> 00:18:56,265
We must do something quickly
to get you out of Brussels.

240
00:19:12,542 --> 00:19:14,109
Miss Cav... Miss Cavell.

241
00:19:14,153 --> 00:19:15,589
I must see her at once!

242
00:19:15,632 --> 00:19:16,633
I'll call [inaudible].

243
00:19:16,677 --> 00:19:17,417
Will you wait in the sitting room?

244
00:19:17,460 --> 00:19:18,287
[inaudible].

245
00:19:18,331 --> 00:19:19,723
Oh!

246
00:19:19,767 --> 00:19:21,377
Oh, my dear!

247
00:19:21,421 --> 00:19:23,771
They're making a house-to-house
search for the prisoners!

248
00:19:23,814 --> 00:19:24,728
Oh, sister.

249
00:19:24,772 --> 00:19:25,729
Please return to the ward.

250
00:19:29,951 --> 00:19:31,387
Now, what is it?

251
00:19:31,431 --> 00:19:32,606
Soldiers.

252
00:19:32,649 --> 00:19:34,216
The soldiers, I heard them talking.

253
00:19:34,260 --> 00:19:37,219
Madame Rappard, you must keep calm!

254
00:19:37,263 --> 00:19:38,177
Where is he?

255
00:19:38,220 --> 00:19:38,960
Where is he?

256
00:19:39,003 --> 00:19:40,527
He's quite safe.

257
00:19:40,570 --> 00:19:41,876
He's up in one of the small wards.

258
00:19:41,919 --> 00:19:43,878
Oh, they'll be sure
to find him there!

259
00:19:43,921 --> 00:19:46,837
They'll be sure to find
him there, [inaudible].

260
00:19:46,881 --> 00:19:48,361
You must rest quietly.

261
00:19:48,404 --> 00:19:50,406
I'll bring him down and
we'll take him to the cellar.

262
00:19:50,450 --> 00:19:51,581
Oh, yes!

263
00:19:51,625 --> 00:19:53,235
Yes, um, that will be much safer!

264
00:19:58,371 --> 00:19:59,328
Halt!

265
00:19:59,372 --> 00:20:00,068
[speaking german]

266
00:20:05,508 --> 00:20:06,205
[inaudible]

267
00:20:17,259 --> 00:20:18,129
Go there, Jean.

268
00:20:21,698 --> 00:20:22,569
Over here.

269
00:20:27,182 --> 00:20:28,966
Now bolt the door inside and don't

270
00:20:29,010 --> 00:20:30,054
open unless you hear my voice.

271
00:20:30,098 --> 00:20:30,751
Yes.

272
00:20:35,756 --> 00:20:36,409
Wait!

273
00:20:42,589 --> 00:20:43,198
Listen up.

274
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:43,851
Help me with this.

275
00:20:47,550 --> 00:20:48,377
[speaking german]

276
00:21:00,171 --> 00:21:03,218
[music playing]

277
00:21:07,570 --> 00:21:09,180
[inaudible].

278
00:21:09,224 --> 00:21:11,095
You cannot go up there without
the permission of the matron.

279
00:21:11,139 --> 00:21:12,314
What is it, sister.

280
00:21:12,358 --> 00:21:13,533
They say they have
an order to search

281
00:21:13,576 --> 00:21:15,926
the home for escape prisoners.

282
00:21:15,970 --> 00:21:17,798
Very well, they will search.

283
00:21:22,585 --> 00:21:23,282
[inaudible]

284
00:21:33,857 --> 00:21:37,687
[music playing]

285
00:22:23,037 --> 00:22:24,473
Good evening, Madame [inaudible].

286
00:22:24,517 --> 00:22:25,909
Why, Mason, what brings you here?

287
00:22:25,953 --> 00:22:28,477
Is there somewhere
we can talk quietly.

288
00:22:28,521 --> 00:22:29,348
Why yes.

289
00:22:29,391 --> 00:22:30,566
Down in the cabin.

290
00:22:30,610 --> 00:22:32,046
There's only my good
for nothing husband

291
00:22:32,089 --> 00:22:34,440
cooking supper down
there, and you know him.

292
00:22:34,483 --> 00:22:35,441
That's as good as being alone.

293
00:22:45,973 --> 00:22:48,410
You remember Madame Rappard?

294
00:22:48,454 --> 00:22:49,977
You mean that poor thing in the bed

295
00:22:50,020 --> 00:22:52,632
next to mine who left
those two nice boys?

296
00:22:52,675 --> 00:22:54,503
It's about the older boy Jean.

297
00:22:54,547 --> 00:22:56,375
He was taken prisoner
but he managed

298
00:22:56,418 --> 00:22:59,160
to escape and make his way
back to his grandmother.

299
00:22:59,203 --> 00:23:02,337
I have been hiding him, and now I

300
00:23:02,381 --> 00:23:05,862
wonder would you help by
taking him across the frontier

301
00:23:05,906 --> 00:23:06,950
into Holland?

302
00:23:06,994 --> 00:23:08,430
Of course I will.

303
00:23:08,474 --> 00:23:09,953
When will he be here?

304
00:23:09,997 --> 00:23:11,607
We're due to leave at
7:00 in the morning.

305
00:23:11,651 --> 00:23:13,783
Oh, I'll see that he gets here.

306
00:23:13,827 --> 00:23:15,132
And when you're
across the frontier,

307
00:23:15,176 --> 00:23:16,699
would you send this
card just to let his

308
00:23:16,743 --> 00:23:18,484
grandmother know that he's safe.

309
00:23:18,527 --> 00:23:19,746
Of course, I will.

310
00:23:19,789 --> 00:23:23,619
[bells chiming]

311
00:24:09,622 --> 00:24:12,581
God bless you, Miss Cavell.

312
00:24:12,625 --> 00:24:16,498
[music playing]

313
00:24:47,050 --> 00:24:48,530
Jean!

314
00:24:48,574 --> 00:24:49,749
We're at the frontier.

315
00:24:49,792 --> 00:24:50,837
They'll search.

316
00:24:50,880 --> 00:24:51,533
Keep quiet.

317
00:25:42,105 --> 00:25:43,585
What happened [inaudible]?

318
00:25:43,629 --> 00:25:44,586
Oh.

319
00:25:44,630 --> 00:25:47,023
In there?

320
00:25:47,067 --> 00:25:49,460
Oh, cognac ala masa moulya.

321
00:25:52,594 --> 00:25:53,900
Well, how about one?

322
00:26:00,515 --> 00:26:01,472
[speaking german]

323
00:26:01,516 --> 00:26:03,910
Bottoms up.

324
00:26:03,953 --> 00:26:04,911
[speaking german]

325
00:26:04,954 --> 00:26:05,781
You're welcome.

326
00:26:09,916 --> 00:26:10,786
Oh, Colonel.

327
00:26:13,528 --> 00:26:16,313
Would you be an angel and
post this card for me?

328
00:26:16,357 --> 00:26:17,271
What?

329
00:26:17,314 --> 00:26:20,056
You post the card for me?

330
00:26:20,100 --> 00:26:21,841
Oh, yeah. [speaking german]

331
00:26:21,884 --> 00:26:22,624
Yes.

332
00:26:22,668 --> 00:26:24,626
Thank you, General.

333
00:26:24,670 --> 00:26:28,499
[music playing]

334
00:27:11,804 --> 00:27:12,761
Madame la Countess!

335
00:27:12,805 --> 00:27:14,284
Madame la Countess?

336
00:27:14,328 --> 00:27:15,546
[inaudible]

337
00:27:15,590 --> 00:27:16,330
What is.

338
00:27:16,373 --> 00:27:17,723
What is.

339
00:27:17,766 --> 00:27:19,246
[inaudible].

340
00:27:19,289 --> 00:27:21,074
They must have caught
them hiding in the woods.

341
00:27:21,117 --> 00:27:22,597
What are they doing with them?

342
00:27:22,641 --> 00:27:24,555
The... They're going to shoot them!

343
00:27:24,599 --> 00:27:25,469
Madame la Countess!

344
00:27:25,513 --> 00:27:29,386
[speaking german]

345
00:27:29,430 --> 00:27:30,344
Don't be a fool, Charlotte.

346
00:27:30,387 --> 00:27:31,824
Of course they're not.

347
00:27:31,867 --> 00:27:33,608
You don't shoot prisoners of war.

348
00:27:33,652 --> 00:27:36,002
[gun shots]

349
00:27:53,019 --> 00:27:54,934
[inaudible], you hear?

350
00:27:54,977 --> 00:27:56,936
[inaudible]

351
00:27:56,979 --> 00:27:59,068
You foul brute.

352
00:27:59,112 --> 00:28:01,505
You're a disgrace to your uniform.

353
00:28:01,549 --> 00:28:02,681
You hear me?

354
00:28:02,724 --> 00:28:04,944
Do you understand what I'm saying?

355
00:28:04,987 --> 00:28:07,686
I can't speak very
much your language.

356
00:28:07,729 --> 00:28:08,774
But I know what you say.

357
00:28:08,817 --> 00:28:09,731
Then why did you do it?

358
00:28:09,775 --> 00:28:10,819
Why did you do it?

359
00:28:10,863 --> 00:28:13,387
It was commanded.

360
00:28:13,430 --> 00:28:18,784
You mean... oh, my God, [inaudible].

361
00:28:18,827 --> 00:28:20,786
That's horrible!

362
00:28:20,829 --> 00:28:23,702
Madame, war is horrible.

363
00:28:31,753 --> 00:28:34,713
They were in civilian clothing.

364
00:28:34,756 --> 00:28:40,414
According to the log of
war, that makes them spies.

365
00:28:40,457 --> 00:28:43,069
They shot them.

366
00:28:43,112 --> 00:28:46,681
I never thought I'd
live to see such things.

367
00:28:46,725 --> 00:28:48,335
Horrible.

368
00:28:48,378 --> 00:28:50,511
Everywhere, all
over the countryside

369
00:28:50,554 --> 00:28:53,732
they're hiding out
in barns and ditches.

370
00:28:53,775 --> 00:28:57,387
Most of them wounded, sick.

371
00:28:57,431 --> 00:28:59,912
Charlotte, told me that if you
go to the far side of the woods

372
00:28:59,955 --> 00:29:02,784
you can hear them
moaning, crying for help.

373
00:29:09,356 --> 00:29:10,487
Is the matron in?

374
00:29:10,531 --> 00:29:11,271
Yes.

375
00:29:11,314 --> 00:29:12,446
Can I see her?

376
00:29:12,489 --> 00:29:13,839
Oh, I have such good news for her.

377
00:29:13,882 --> 00:29:15,188
Well, I'm sure she'll
see you, Madame Rappard.

378
00:29:15,231 --> 00:29:15,928
Thank you.

379
00:29:18,887 --> 00:29:20,280
He's safe!

380
00:29:20,323 --> 00:29:21,237
He's safe!

381
00:29:21,281 --> 00:29:23,109
I just got the card!

382
00:29:23,152 --> 00:29:24,458
Oh, God bless you.

383
00:29:24,501 --> 00:29:25,894
God bless you.

384
00:29:25,938 --> 00:29:30,072
Oh, Madame la Countess,
she saved my boys' life.

385
00:29:30,116 --> 00:29:34,990
God will bless her.
[crying] God will bless her.

386
00:29:35,034 --> 00:29:38,907
[music playing]

387
00:30:31,264 --> 00:30:33,222
JEAN [VOICEOVER]: I'm
one of the lucky ones.

388
00:30:33,266 --> 00:30:35,529
You can see some of the
others lying wounded

389
00:30:35,572 --> 00:30:37,226
in trenches and shell holes.

390
00:30:37,270 --> 00:30:40,099
If you can only do something
for them like you did for me.

391
00:30:40,142 --> 00:30:41,665
MADAME COUNTESS [VOICEOVER]:
Charlotte told me

392
00:30:41,709 --> 00:30:43,493
that if you go to the
far side of the woods

393
00:30:43,537 --> 00:30:46,845
you can hear them
moaning, crying for help.

394
00:30:50,457 --> 00:30:54,809
[music playing]

395
00:31:33,065 --> 00:31:35,763
[inaudible], an
angel from heaven.

396
00:31:35,806 --> 00:31:37,808
Not quite, but I'm well on my way.

397
00:31:44,467 --> 00:31:47,253
Snatched from the jaws
of death, I called it.

398
00:31:47,296 --> 00:31:49,255
[inaudible] you'll be
quite safe in the ward

399
00:31:49,298 --> 00:31:50,778
as civilian patients.

400
00:31:50,821 --> 00:31:52,345
And then we shall arrange
to get you into Holland.

401
00:31:52,388 --> 00:31:54,477
I'm afraid it will be some
time before you can move,

402
00:31:54,521 --> 00:31:55,739
though... your foot is septic.

403
00:31:55,783 --> 00:31:56,523
Go on, is it?

404
00:31:56,566 --> 00:31:58,742
Yes. [inaudible].

405
00:31:58,786 --> 00:32:01,267
Bungey, the name is, Miss... Private

406
00:32:01,310 --> 00:32:02,921
Bungey of the East Kent regiment,

407
00:32:02,964 --> 00:32:04,487
commonly known as the Buffs.

408
00:32:04,531 --> 00:32:05,967
We'll have to be
especially careful, Bungey,

409
00:32:06,011 --> 00:32:07,969
or your English will give you away.

410
00:32:08,013 --> 00:32:09,623
Ello, ello, ello.

411
00:32:09,666 --> 00:32:10,667
Woah.

412
00:32:10,711 --> 00:32:12,321
Careful over the cobbles, cabby.

413
00:32:12,365 --> 00:32:14,323
Yes, it is a little unsteady,
but the Countess has never

414
00:32:14,367 --> 00:32:15,672
driven an ambulance before.

415
00:32:15,716 --> 00:32:17,283
Oh, I see.

416
00:32:17,326 --> 00:32:18,023
Blimey!

417
00:32:39,261 --> 00:32:40,828
Oh, sister.

418
00:32:40,871 --> 00:32:42,656
I have four cases outside I
wish to isolate in a small ward.

419
00:32:42,699 --> 00:32:44,223
Will you see that it's made ready?

420
00:32:44,266 --> 00:32:45,485
Yes, matron.

421
00:32:45,528 --> 00:32:47,966
Um, there's a villager to see you.

422
00:32:48,009 --> 00:32:49,054
I'll deal with that later.

423
00:32:49,097 --> 00:32:51,970
But the officer said it was urgent.

424
00:32:52,013 --> 00:32:53,101
- Officer?
- Yes.

425
00:32:53,145 --> 00:32:54,102
He's a German officer.

426
00:32:54,146 --> 00:32:56,235
He's in your sitting room.

427
00:32:56,278 --> 00:32:57,236
What is his regiment?

428
00:32:57,279 --> 00:32:58,585
He didn't say.

429
00:32:58,628 --> 00:33:01,588
He said he wished to
speak to you personally.

430
00:33:01,631 --> 00:33:02,676
Very well. I will see him.

431
00:33:02,719 --> 00:33:03,459
Attend to the ward, sister.

432
00:33:03,503 --> 00:33:04,156
Yes, ma'am.

433
00:33:11,076 --> 00:33:13,034
An officer has called to see me.

434
00:33:13,078 --> 00:33:15,123
Drive around the back of the
house and wait for me there.

435
00:33:25,046 --> 00:33:25,568
Madame Cavell?

436
00:33:29,311 --> 00:33:32,619
I'm Dr. Gunther of
the Army Medical Corp.

437
00:33:32,662 --> 00:33:34,360
We are transferring the first
contingent of our wounded

438
00:33:34,403 --> 00:33:36,057
here today.

439
00:33:36,101 --> 00:33:38,842
You will remove all civilian
patients to their own houses.

440
00:33:38,886 --> 00:33:42,020
All Belgium, French and
British wounded must be handed

441
00:33:42,063 --> 00:33:44,065
over to the German authorities.

442
00:33:44,109 --> 00:33:45,414
Very well, Dr. Gunther.

443
00:34:11,962 --> 00:34:13,486
They're bringing German
wounded into the home.

444
00:34:13,529 --> 00:34:15,575
Well, what are we going
to do with these men?

445
00:34:15,618 --> 00:34:17,533
We can keep them down in
the cellar for a few days.

446
00:34:17,577 --> 00:34:18,969
That's where I keep Jean Rappard.

447
00:34:41,992 --> 00:34:45,344
All Belgium and French
soldiers hiding in the town

448
00:34:45,387 --> 00:34:49,348
are to be delivered up
as prisoners of war.

449
00:34:49,391 --> 00:34:52,090
They don't know us
yet, Madame Rappard.

450
00:34:52,133 --> 00:34:54,353
They don't know us
yet, [inaudible].

451
00:35:10,543 --> 00:35:13,111
Remember [inaudible]?

452
00:35:13,154 --> 00:35:16,026
What are you looking
for, my friend?

453
00:35:16,070 --> 00:35:19,117
They've rolled into [inaudible].

454
00:35:19,160 --> 00:35:21,162
How many?

455
00:35:21,206 --> 00:35:21,728
Four.

456
00:35:47,667 --> 00:35:51,018
[music playing]

457
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:57,938
[gasping]

458
00:35:57,981 --> 00:36:00,201
I'm afraid it's hopeless.

459
00:36:00,245 --> 00:36:03,552
Just a few minutes now.

460
00:36:03,596 --> 00:36:05,032
Poor boy.

461
00:36:05,075 --> 00:36:07,382
So young.

462
00:36:07,426 --> 00:36:13,910
[speaking german]

463
00:36:13,954 --> 00:36:16,304
What is he saying?

464
00:36:16,348 --> 00:36:19,264
He thinks he's a prisoner of war.

465
00:36:19,307 --> 00:36:22,702
He wants to be set free.

466
00:36:22,745 --> 00:36:28,316
[speaking german]

467
00:36:28,360 --> 00:36:29,752
You shall be free.

468
00:36:33,365 --> 00:36:39,284
[speaking german]

469
00:36:39,327 --> 00:36:40,720
Very soon now.

470
00:37:04,874 --> 00:37:06,136
Sorry if I'm late, ladies.

471
00:37:06,180 --> 00:37:07,573
Oh, no, Madame la Countess.

472
00:37:07,616 --> 00:37:08,487
We were learning.

473
00:37:08,530 --> 00:37:09,531
Eager for your work, eh?

474
00:37:09,575 --> 00:37:10,750
Yes, indeed, ma'am.

475
00:37:10,793 --> 00:37:11,446
Good.

476
00:37:22,109 --> 00:37:22,979
He's sleeping.

477
00:37:37,559 --> 00:37:40,214
If I can be of any help, please
don't hesitate to send for me.

478
00:37:40,258 --> 00:37:40,910
Thanks.

479
00:37:53,967 --> 00:37:55,403
What is it, nurse?

480
00:37:55,447 --> 00:37:56,926
The Countess is here.

481
00:37:56,970 --> 00:37:59,929
She's in your private sitting room.

482
00:37:59,973 --> 00:38:03,933
I have to go down to the
small isolation ward first.

483
00:38:03,977 --> 00:38:05,326
Please stay here, nurse.

484
00:38:32,397 --> 00:38:34,312
Some friends have
promised to help and

485
00:38:34,355 --> 00:38:37,010
we're making plans to leave.

486
00:38:37,053 --> 00:38:38,316
Tomorrow night, I hope.

487
00:38:38,359 --> 00:38:39,795
Use the identification
cards coming through.

488
00:38:39,839 --> 00:38:40,796
[speaking french], bien.

489
00:38:40,840 --> 00:38:41,580
Merci.

490
00:38:41,623 --> 00:38:43,146
How about me?

491
00:38:43,190 --> 00:38:44,365
Oh, no Bungey.

492
00:38:44,409 --> 00:38:45,671
You must wait until
your foot is better.

493
00:38:45,714 --> 00:38:47,586
I thought you said it
wasn't skeptic anymore.

494
00:38:47,629 --> 00:38:50,197
No, I didn't, but you'll be
too dangerous for the others.

495
00:38:50,240 --> 00:38:51,372
I'm sorry, Bungey.

496
00:38:51,416 --> 00:38:52,199
Good night.

497
00:38:52,242 --> 00:38:53,679
Bonsoir.

498
00:38:53,722 --> 00:38:56,377
[inaudible], Bungey.

499
00:38:56,421 --> 00:38:57,073
[inaudible]

500
00:39:02,644 --> 00:39:04,603
Good evening, Countess.

501
00:39:04,646 --> 00:39:06,605
Only three of the
men will be leaving.

502
00:39:06,648 --> 00:39:08,607
The English lad is not
fit for the journey.

503
00:39:08,650 --> 00:39:10,130
He must go later.

504
00:39:10,173 --> 00:39:12,001
Were you able to get the
identification cards?

505
00:39:28,235 --> 00:39:28,888
[inaudible]

506
00:39:31,543 --> 00:39:34,067
Madame Moulin, when
can barge will leave?

507
00:39:34,110 --> 00:39:35,982
Whenever you wish, matron.

508
00:39:36,025 --> 00:39:37,331
Tomorrow night then.

509
00:39:37,375 --> 00:39:39,768
And Madame Rappard,
is everything ready?

510
00:39:39,812 --> 00:39:41,204
Everything is ready, matron.

511
00:39:41,248 --> 00:39:43,859
Francois will guide
them to the back.

512
00:39:43,903 --> 00:39:46,296
Francois will watch
the back of the house.

513
00:39:46,340 --> 00:39:48,734
You will watch the front.

514
00:39:48,777 --> 00:39:51,258
[bells ringing]

515
00:39:51,301 --> 00:39:52,651
Courage, Madame Rappard.

516
00:40:27,599 --> 00:40:29,557
You have your identification cards?

517
00:40:29,601 --> 00:40:30,950
Oui Madame la Countess.

518
00:40:42,527 --> 00:40:43,484
[knock on door]

519
00:40:43,528 --> 00:40:44,180
[inaudible]

520
00:40:49,490 --> 00:40:50,839
Four men [inaudible].

521
00:40:55,104 --> 00:40:56,279
All clear.

522
00:40:56,323 --> 00:40:57,455
Follow your instructions implicitly

523
00:40:57,498 --> 00:41:00,327
and you'll soon be out of danger.

524
00:41:00,370 --> 00:41:01,502
Bon voyage.

525
00:41:01,546 --> 00:41:02,198
[inaudible]

526
00:41:08,117 --> 00:41:10,032
[inaudible]

527
00:41:10,076 --> 00:41:12,513
Well, Bungey, your turn.

528
00:41:12,557 --> 00:41:14,515
Don't think so, [inaudible].

529
00:41:14,559 --> 00:41:17,431
Unkind word and I shall
cry my bloomin' eyes out.

530
00:41:30,096 --> 00:41:32,794
Would you be an angel
again, [inaudible]?

531
00:41:32,838 --> 00:41:33,403
[speaking german]

532
00:41:47,679 --> 00:41:51,509
[music playing]

533
00:42:08,482 --> 00:42:11,224
Gentlemen, the new military
governor of Brussels,

534
00:42:11,267 --> 00:42:14,706
[inaudible] General [inaudible].

535
00:42:14,749 --> 00:42:19,188
General, [inaudible], head
of the political department

536
00:42:19,232 --> 00:42:20,799
[inaudible].

537
00:42:20,842 --> 00:42:24,193
Captain Heinrichs, Chief of
the [inaudible] espionage.

538
00:42:24,237 --> 00:42:25,586
Lt. Schmidt, [inaudible].

539
00:42:36,249 --> 00:42:37,598
Captain Heinrichs, [inaudible].

540
00:42:49,697 --> 00:42:52,178
Captain Heinrichs, you
are head of [inaudible].

541
00:42:52,221 --> 00:42:54,833
Yavolt, Excellence.

542
00:42:54,876 --> 00:42:55,747
Will you look at that.

543
00:43:01,535 --> 00:43:03,842
Would you mind, Excellence, tell me

544
00:43:03,885 --> 00:43:05,408
how this came into your hands?

545
00:43:05,452 --> 00:43:07,410
It was taken from
a derelict Belgium

546
00:43:07,454 --> 00:43:09,238
soldier who was captured last night

547
00:43:09,282 --> 00:43:11,850
on the outskirts of Brussels.

548
00:43:11,893 --> 00:43:15,505
But Excellence, this should
have come directly to me.

549
00:43:15,549 --> 00:43:18,378
I have given instruction
that all papers referring

550
00:43:18,421 --> 00:43:21,250
to the traffic of escape
prisoners and derelict soldiers

551
00:43:21,294 --> 00:43:23,209
shall pass through my hand.

552
00:43:23,252 --> 00:43:24,514
[inaudible], Excellence...

553
00:43:24,558 --> 00:43:26,995
I want no argument,
Captain Heinrichs.

554
00:43:27,039 --> 00:43:28,910
I have been sent to
[inaudible] to restore

555
00:43:28,954 --> 00:43:30,390
discipline amongst the population

556
00:43:30,433 --> 00:43:31,696
and the [inaudible] occupation.

557
00:43:31,739 --> 00:43:33,523
And I mean to do so.

558
00:43:33,567 --> 00:43:35,003
This traffic and escape prisoners

559
00:43:35,047 --> 00:43:36,570
has been going on long enough!

560
00:43:36,614 --> 00:43:39,399
I am convinced there is
an organization behind it.

561
00:43:39,442 --> 00:43:41,140
This map is the clear proof.

562
00:43:41,183 --> 00:43:43,490
Unravel this, and we'll get to
the heart of your organization.

563
00:43:48,364 --> 00:43:58,679
[singing]

564
00:43:58,723 --> 00:44:00,725
One of these days, I
suppose these simple Germans

565
00:44:00,768 --> 00:44:02,640
will wonder, if no other cargo goes

566
00:44:02,683 --> 00:44:03,684
over the frontier, [inaudible].

567
00:44:07,557 --> 00:44:10,952
[inaudible] poker player,
I'd say we had a full house.

568
00:44:10,996 --> 00:44:11,953
Patrick Doland?

569
00:44:11,997 --> 00:44:12,954
Yes, ma'am.

570
00:44:12,998 --> 00:44:14,129
Issac Rosenthal?

571
00:44:14,173 --> 00:44:14,913
Yes, [inaudible].

572
00:44:14,956 --> 00:44:15,914
James Colsac?

573
00:44:15,957 --> 00:44:17,611
Ey, [inaudible].

574
00:44:17,655 --> 00:44:18,481
What about me, Miss?

575
00:44:18,525 --> 00:44:19,526
Can't I go on the next load?

576
00:44:19,961 --> 00:44:21,397
We'll see how you are, Bungey.

577
00:44:21,441 --> 00:44:22,398
Oh, I'm all right.

578
00:44:22,442 --> 00:44:25,314
Look at me!

579
00:44:25,358 --> 00:44:26,228
London [inaudible] it is.

580
00:44:30,276 --> 00:44:31,233
It's all right.

581
00:44:31,277 --> 00:44:32,017
It's all right.

582
00:44:32,060 --> 00:44:33,714
I did it on purpose.

583
00:44:33,758 --> 00:44:36,630
[inaudible]

584
00:44:36,674 --> 00:44:38,588
Oh, I'm not, am I?

585
00:44:38,632 --> 00:44:40,242
Now will all those whose
names I've called give me

586
00:44:40,286 --> 00:44:41,940
their Army identification card.

587
00:44:47,772 --> 00:44:49,208
Good night, you all.

588
00:44:49,251 --> 00:44:51,645
Good night.

589
00:44:51,689 --> 00:44:53,778
Here.

590
00:44:53,821 --> 00:44:54,517
Thank you.

591
00:45:00,001 --> 00:45:01,307
You know, [inaudible].

592
00:45:01,350 --> 00:45:02,961
I don't want to grumble, sir.

593
00:45:03,004 --> 00:45:05,485
I [inaudible] with a nice
square meal after [inaudible].

594
00:45:05,528 --> 00:45:07,008
We're lucky to get in at all.

595
00:45:07,052 --> 00:45:08,444
It must be very
different [inaudible].

596
00:45:08,488 --> 00:45:09,141
[inaudible].

597
00:45:11,534 --> 00:45:15,843
But what wouldn't I give for
a nice pint of [inaudible].

598
00:45:15,887 --> 00:45:18,846
Perhaps [inaudible].

599
00:45:18,890 --> 00:45:21,936
And then perhaps a nice
stable kidney pudding

600
00:45:21,980 --> 00:45:23,895
with plenty of
kidneys and the gravy

601
00:45:23,938 --> 00:45:25,461
running all over the base.

602
00:45:31,424 --> 00:45:33,774
How many can you take on
the next trip, Madame Moulin.

603
00:45:33,818 --> 00:45:34,949
As many as you like.

604
00:45:34,993 --> 00:45:36,951
I don't think these [inaudible].

605
00:45:36,995 --> 00:45:39,432
There's seven more
will be here on Friday.

606
00:45:39,475 --> 00:45:41,260
Then 11 must go tomorrow night.

607
00:45:41,303 --> 00:45:42,827
I can take them.

608
00:45:42,870 --> 00:45:46,047
[inaudible] off and
transferred to the German

609
00:45:46,091 --> 00:45:47,440
identification cards.

610
00:45:47,483 --> 00:45:49,007
Can that be done by tomorrow night?

611
00:45:49,050 --> 00:45:50,399
Yes.

612
00:45:50,443 --> 00:45:51,749
You, Madame Rappard?

613
00:45:51,792 --> 00:45:53,402
It's all arranged.

614
00:45:53,446 --> 00:45:56,928
Francois and I will guide you
as far as the [inaudible].

615
00:45:56,971 --> 00:45:58,886
And the other boys, we'll take
them on the tram [inaudible].

616
00:46:24,912 --> 00:46:26,305
Mama, look out!

617
00:46:38,883 --> 00:46:41,581
[music playing]

618
00:46:41,624 --> 00:46:42,277
[inaudible]!

619
00:46:58,511 --> 00:46:59,468
British!

620
00:46:59,512 --> 00:47:01,209
Yes.

621
00:47:01,253 --> 00:47:03,168
We must take him to Brussels.

622
00:47:03,211 --> 00:47:04,169
Oui.

623
00:47:04,212 --> 00:47:05,083
We must hide him.

624
00:47:55,089 --> 00:47:58,049
[speaking german]

625
00:47:58,092 --> 00:47:58,658
[speaking german]

626
00:48:45,487 --> 00:48:47,837
[inaudible], clean
up [inaudible].

627
00:49:24,570 --> 00:49:25,223
[inaudible]

628
00:50:02,216 --> 00:50:04,175
Edith, my dear, this
must be the last.

629
00:50:04,218 --> 00:50:05,698
We must stop it.

630
00:50:05,741 --> 00:50:07,308
How can we stop?

631
00:50:07,352 --> 00:50:08,788
While any of these men
are needing our help,

632
00:50:08,831 --> 00:50:10,137
we must go on.

633
00:50:10,181 --> 00:50:12,618
If one of them should
be caught and shot

634
00:50:12,661 --> 00:50:14,881
will be our fault. Swab.

635
00:50:22,280 --> 00:50:24,238
But we searched the
whole wood, Herr Captain

636
00:50:24,282 --> 00:50:25,631
and can find no trace of him.

637
00:50:29,113 --> 00:50:30,592
Lt. Schmidt.

638
00:50:30,636 --> 00:50:32,638
Offer a reward, 500
francs, for any information

639
00:50:32,681 --> 00:50:34,292
leading to his
arrest, dead or alive.

640
00:50:34,335 --> 00:50:35,945
Search every hospital, and instruct

641
00:50:35,989 --> 00:50:40,602
all doctors and officers to
report any unusual cases.

642
00:50:40,646 --> 00:50:41,386
Yavolt, Herr Captain.

643
00:50:44,998 --> 00:50:47,914
Lean heavily on me.

644
00:50:47,957 --> 00:50:49,394
That's right.

645
00:50:49,437 --> 00:50:52,875
[inaudible], but I must
get you downstairs.

646
00:50:52,919 --> 00:50:55,226
If we meet anyone on
the way, don't speak.

647
00:51:10,676 --> 00:51:13,418
Ah, Lt. von Schultz.

648
00:51:13,461 --> 00:51:15,724
Your promotion is overdue.

649
00:51:15,768 --> 00:51:17,117
Donka, el Captain.

650
00:51:17,161 --> 00:51:20,947
Now this map indicates
a secret organization

651
00:51:20,990 --> 00:51:24,559
going on [inaudible]
escape prisoners.

652
00:51:24,603 --> 00:51:25,734
Yavolt, Herr Kapitan.

653
00:51:25,778 --> 00:51:27,780
And I'm relying on you to uncover

654
00:51:27,823 --> 00:51:31,871
this entire organization,
uh, Captain Schultz.

655
00:51:35,092 --> 00:51:36,267
I will earn my
promotion, Herr Captain.

656
00:51:47,191 --> 00:51:49,584
Madame la Countess.

657
00:51:49,628 --> 00:51:52,109
Another one has arrived.

658
00:51:52,152 --> 00:51:54,067
[inaudible] is he stable?

659
00:51:54,111 --> 00:51:55,634
No, Madame la Countess.

660
00:51:55,677 --> 00:51:56,939
This one came to the lodge.

661
00:51:56,983 --> 00:51:59,855
He's waiting outside in the hall.

662
00:51:59,899 --> 00:52:00,769
Ask him in.

663
00:52:13,521 --> 00:52:15,654
Madame la Countess,
you have the reputation

664
00:52:15,697 --> 00:52:17,612
for being a good friend.

665
00:52:17,656 --> 00:52:19,005
Well?

666
00:52:19,048 --> 00:52:22,400
I have escaped from
a German prison camp.

667
00:52:22,443 --> 00:52:24,489
From what prison
camp did you escape?

668
00:52:24,532 --> 00:52:26,186
[inaudible]

669
00:52:26,230 --> 00:52:27,840
What nationality are you?

670
00:52:27,883 --> 00:52:29,711
French.

671
00:52:29,755 --> 00:52:32,236
What do you expect
me to do for you?

672
00:52:32,279 --> 00:52:35,935
Help me to get out of
Belgium and back into France.

673
00:52:35,978 --> 00:52:40,069
I am anxious to fight
again for my company.

674
00:52:40,113 --> 00:52:44,987
Charlotte, take care
of this poor man.

675
00:52:45,031 --> 00:52:47,947
See that he has food
and drink, and lock

676
00:52:47,990 --> 00:52:51,211
the kitchen so that he won't
be disturbed while he's there.

677
00:52:51,255 --> 00:52:52,865
Wee, Madame la Countess.

678
00:52:52,908 --> 00:52:54,693
Merci, Madame la Countess.

679
00:52:54,736 --> 00:52:55,781
This way, please.

680
00:53:13,190 --> 00:53:17,455
Brussels 9046.

681
00:53:17,498 --> 00:53:19,500
This Brussels 9046.

682
00:53:19,544 --> 00:53:23,722
May I speak to the chief of police?

683
00:53:23,765 --> 00:53:26,115
This is the Countess Mavon.

684
00:53:26,159 --> 00:53:30,337
Would you send an escort to
the Chateau Mavon at once.

685
00:53:30,381 --> 00:53:34,602
I have a French refugee
prisoner of war here.

686
00:53:34,646 --> 00:53:36,604
I'm keeping him locked in
the kitchen until you arrive.

687
00:53:40,129 --> 00:53:41,479
Not at all.

688
00:53:41,522 --> 00:53:43,437
It's a very great pleasure.

689
00:54:07,113 --> 00:54:07,766
Cavell.

690
00:54:24,870 --> 00:54:27,046
We're being watched, my dear.

691
00:54:27,089 --> 00:54:29,788
I was followed here by the
man talking to those workmen.

692
00:54:32,704 --> 00:54:35,446
And last night a stool pigeon
flew into my [inaudible].

693
00:54:35,489 --> 00:54:36,795
What did you do?

694
00:54:36,838 --> 00:54:38,666
Pinched his wings
a bit and handed him

695
00:54:38,710 --> 00:54:40,146
over to the German authorities.

696
00:54:40,189 --> 00:54:42,279
I thought they'd understand
the same language.

697
00:54:42,322 --> 00:54:44,368
He had the loveliest
Franco Prussian accent

698
00:54:44,411 --> 00:54:45,499
you've ever heard, my dear.

699
00:54:49,111 --> 00:54:50,461
Francois Rappard.

700
00:54:54,116 --> 00:54:54,769
One.

701
00:55:00,732 --> 00:55:02,124
What are you looking
for, my friend?

702
00:55:02,168 --> 00:55:03,952
A safe road and a quick journey.

703
00:55:03,996 --> 00:55:04,736
Who sent you?

704
00:55:04,779 --> 00:55:05,606
Number 33.

705
00:55:12,787 --> 00:55:14,180
Read it again.

706
00:55:14,223 --> 00:55:17,096
"I have almost earned my
promotion, Herr Kapitan.

707
00:55:17,139 --> 00:55:20,491
But I have not yet reached the
heart of the organization."

708
00:55:20,534 --> 00:55:21,622
How [inaudible]?

709
00:55:21,666 --> 00:55:23,015
Through Dr. Gunther.

710
00:55:23,058 --> 00:55:25,104
Was addressed to him
to be delivered here.

711
00:55:25,147 --> 00:55:25,931
Where is Countess?

712
00:55:25,974 --> 00:55:28,586
At 149 [inaudible].

713
00:55:28,629 --> 00:55:29,630
Oh, let me see.

714
00:55:29,674 --> 00:55:31,110
That's the nursing home run by...

715
00:55:31,153 --> 00:55:32,067
The English woman, Cavell.

716
00:55:32,111 --> 00:55:32,807
I'm sure.

717
00:56:04,448 --> 00:56:08,321
[buzzer sound]

718
00:56:21,508 --> 00:56:22,466
Dr. Gunther.

719
00:56:22,509 --> 00:56:23,945
This note.

720
00:56:23,989 --> 00:56:25,947
I found it on my desk.

721
00:56:25,991 --> 00:56:28,994
It must have been put there
by someone who knows the house.

722
00:56:29,037 --> 00:56:30,952
Have you seen anything
suspicious here?

723
00:56:30,996 --> 00:56:32,911
No, Herr Kapitan.

724
00:56:32,954 --> 00:56:34,347
I've carried out the instructions,

725
00:56:34,391 --> 00:56:35,304
but I've seen nothing.

726
00:56:35,348 --> 00:56:37,263
What about the woman Cavell?

727
00:56:37,306 --> 00:56:40,005
She's cooperative
and a generous person.

728
00:56:40,048 --> 00:56:41,789
[inaudible] she's an English
woman and must be watched.

729
00:57:06,031 --> 00:57:08,250
Fraulein Cavell.

730
00:57:08,294 --> 00:57:10,557
Where does that lead to?

731
00:57:10,601 --> 00:57:12,429
The boiler house.

732
00:57:12,472 --> 00:57:13,734
I should like to see it.

733
00:57:13,778 --> 00:57:14,605
Very well.

734
00:57:14,648 --> 00:57:15,475
I will take you down myself.

735
00:58:11,052 --> 00:58:13,402
You can hay or sneeze no, man.

736
00:58:13,446 --> 00:58:14,273
I don't want to.

737
00:58:14,316 --> 00:58:15,230
Now I've gone past it.

738
00:58:21,933 --> 00:58:23,630
Fraulein Cavell.

739
00:58:23,674 --> 00:58:25,589
A number of escape
prisoners have been making

740
00:58:25,632 --> 00:58:26,981
their way out of the country.

741
00:58:27,025 --> 00:58:28,679
It would be a very serious matter

742
00:58:28,722 --> 00:58:29,941
for those who engage
in this traffic

743
00:58:29,984 --> 00:58:31,551
if they should be caught.

744
00:58:31,595 --> 00:58:34,598
Whether they were men or
women, Fraulein Cavell,

745
00:58:34,641 --> 00:58:36,208
they would incur the
severest penalties.

746
00:58:38,819 --> 00:58:41,430
It is our duty.

747
00:58:41,474 --> 00:58:42,214
It is your duty.

748
00:59:01,538 --> 00:59:03,365
Matron, are you all right?

749
00:59:06,499 --> 00:59:08,414
So tired.

750
00:59:08,457 --> 00:59:10,024
It's too much for you, matron.

751
00:59:10,068 --> 00:59:10,851
Why don't you lay down...

752
00:59:10,895 --> 00:59:12,592
[inaudible] suspect.

753
00:59:12,636 --> 00:59:14,072
These men are in great danger.

754
00:59:14,115 --> 00:59:16,204
We must get them away at once.

755
00:59:16,248 --> 00:59:18,163
[inaudible], he's
not fit to be moved.

756
00:59:18,206 --> 00:59:19,817
Send word to the
Countess, Madame Rappard,

757
00:59:19,860 --> 00:59:20,818
Madame Moulin for tonight.

758
00:59:20,861 --> 00:59:21,558
Yes, matron.

759
00:59:27,651 --> 00:59:29,609
Now you know the routine.

760
00:59:29,653 --> 00:59:31,350
You follow the guide
and in pointed groups

761
00:59:31,393 --> 00:59:32,743
as far as Moulin.

762
00:59:32,786 --> 00:59:34,745
There you will be handed
over to the other guide.

763
00:59:34,788 --> 00:59:36,573
You have your identification cards?

764
00:59:36,616 --> 00:59:38,183
Yes.

765
00:59:38,226 --> 00:59:41,490
You know the password, safe
road and a quick journey.

766
00:59:41,534 --> 00:59:43,405
Now I'll see if all is clear.

767
00:59:57,942 --> 00:59:58,899
Goodbye, Bungey.

768
00:59:58,943 --> 01:00:00,335
Don't forget your promise.

769
01:00:00,379 --> 01:00:01,859
Not a drink till you are
safely across the frontier.

770
01:00:01,902 --> 01:00:03,034
Nor you, Pierre.

771
01:00:03,077 --> 01:00:04,818
No, we won't forget, Miss Cavell.

772
01:00:04,862 --> 01:00:06,385
There's other things that I won't

773
01:00:06,428 --> 01:00:08,692
forget neither... no
[inaudible], none of us.

774
01:00:08,735 --> 01:00:09,867
God bless you.

775
01:00:09,910 --> 01:00:10,650
Bye.

776
01:00:10,694 --> 01:00:11,477
Bye.

777
01:00:11,520 --> 01:00:12,565
Au Revoir, Pierre.

778
01:00:21,966 --> 01:00:23,010
Godspeed, Jacques.

779
01:00:23,054 --> 01:00:23,707
Bonsoir.

780
01:00:43,335 --> 01:00:43,988
Bungey.

781
01:00:48,514 --> 01:00:49,471
Oh.

782
01:00:49,515 --> 01:00:50,472
[inaudible]

783
01:00:50,516 --> 01:00:51,430
What's that for?

784
01:00:51,473 --> 01:00:52,300
Your supper.

785
01:00:52,344 --> 01:00:53,650
Oh.

786
01:00:53,693 --> 01:00:55,042
I thought that you wanted
me to get inside it.

787
01:00:55,086 --> 01:00:55,869
It's a good one.

788
01:00:55,913 --> 01:00:56,696
Comic.

789
01:00:56,740 --> 01:00:57,566
I'll see you later.

790
01:00:57,610 --> 01:00:58,655
Ey.

791
01:00:58,698 --> 01:00:59,786
And maybe bring you some cognac.

792
01:00:59,830 --> 01:01:00,787
Oh.

793
01:01:00,831 --> 01:01:02,484
That's different, isn't it?

794
01:01:02,528 --> 01:01:04,399
Here, here, what about Pierre
and the other [inaudible]?

795
01:01:04,443 --> 01:01:07,751
I'll give them just five more
minutes and then we're off.

796
01:01:07,794 --> 01:01:08,708
[inaudible].

797
01:01:08,752 --> 01:01:09,622
I wonder what [inaudible].

798
01:01:12,669 --> 01:01:14,366
Fantastic!

799
01:01:14,409 --> 01:01:17,717
The whole of the German secret
service fooled by a few women!

800
01:01:17,761 --> 01:01:21,025
Yes, [inaudible].

801
01:01:21,068 --> 01:01:23,114
And I can tell you more than that.

802
01:01:23,157 --> 01:01:24,637
I'm sure you can.

803
01:01:24,681 --> 01:01:25,594
You're the clever one.

804
01:01:25,638 --> 01:01:26,639
Yes.

805
01:01:26,683 --> 01:01:28,206
And shall I tell you something?

806
01:01:28,249 --> 01:01:29,642
Yes.

807
01:01:29,686 --> 01:01:30,730
You know who I am?

808
01:01:30,774 --> 01:01:32,166
No.

809
01:01:32,210 --> 01:01:35,866
I am Captain William Schultz of the

810
01:01:35,909 --> 01:01:37,215
German military intelligence.

811
01:01:47,181 --> 01:01:48,139
How many?

812
01:01:48,182 --> 01:01:48,835
One.

813
01:02:02,414 --> 01:02:04,590
Madame la Countess,
you will come with me

814
01:02:04,633 --> 01:02:05,460
to Captain Heinrichs' office.

815
01:02:10,422 --> 01:02:14,426
England, and to
play some cricket,

816
01:02:14,469 --> 01:02:19,213
and to see [inaudible] again.

817
01:02:19,257 --> 01:02:21,128
Norridge.

818
01:02:21,172 --> 01:02:24,175
Yes, do you know it, matron?

819
01:02:24,218 --> 01:02:26,612
It's my home.

820
01:02:26,655 --> 01:02:27,526
Give it my love.

821
01:02:36,448 --> 01:02:40,321
I demand to know why
I've been brought here.

822
01:02:40,365 --> 01:02:43,760
You do not know?

823
01:02:43,803 --> 01:02:45,718
I do not.

824
01:02:45,762 --> 01:02:48,590
You are under arrest for
assisting prisoners of war

825
01:02:48,634 --> 01:02:49,809
out of the country.

826
01:02:49,853 --> 01:02:51,593
Now, all you do is follow the guide

827
01:02:51,637 --> 01:02:53,291
and you will soon be safe.

828
01:02:53,334 --> 01:02:54,161
Yes, matron.

829
01:02:54,205 --> 01:02:56,076
I understand perfectly.

830
01:02:56,120 --> 01:02:58,818
Don't you ever want to
go back home, not here

831
01:02:58,862 --> 01:03:01,560
among all these foreigners?

832
01:03:01,603 --> 01:03:04,041
There's only one
human race, my dear.

833
01:03:04,084 --> 01:03:06,565
Yes, I suppose that's true.

834
01:03:06,608 --> 01:03:09,307
What would they do if they found
out you had gotten me here?

835
01:03:09,350 --> 01:03:11,788
I mean ought'n you to
hand me over to them

836
01:03:11,831 --> 01:03:13,354
now that I'm all right again?

837
01:03:13,398 --> 01:03:15,008
You think I've nursed
you back to life

838
01:03:15,052 --> 01:03:16,749
to hand you over to be shot?

839
01:03:16,793 --> 01:03:20,057
I'll see if everything's ready.

840
01:03:20,100 --> 01:03:21,362
How dare you.

841
01:03:21,406 --> 01:03:23,625
Officer [inaudible],
[speaking german].

842
01:03:28,761 --> 01:03:31,111
Do you know this man?

843
01:03:31,155 --> 01:03:32,025
Or this?

844
01:03:36,160 --> 01:03:39,032
An informer and the worm.

845
01:03:41,687 --> 01:03:44,690
I congratulate you on your
friends, Herr Captain.

846
01:03:47,824 --> 01:03:50,261
We'll have to go without
your identification card.

847
01:03:50,304 --> 01:03:51,740
Nothing's gone wrong, matron.

848
01:03:51,784 --> 01:03:52,785
Oh, no, no.

849
01:03:52,829 --> 01:03:53,917
You have your emergency ration?

850
01:03:53,960 --> 01:03:54,918
- Yes, ma'am.
- Your money?

851
01:03:54,961 --> 01:03:55,744
Yes.

852
01:03:55,788 --> 01:03:56,658
Come along then.

853
01:04:06,755 --> 01:04:10,194
All clear.

854
01:04:10,237 --> 01:04:11,195
Goodbye, Richard.

855
01:04:11,238 --> 01:04:12,674
Goodbye, matron.

856
01:04:12,718 --> 01:04:15,155
I shall never be able
to thank you enough.

857
01:04:15,199 --> 01:04:16,069
God bless you.

858
01:04:57,676 --> 01:05:00,157
[inaudible] Miss Cavell,
I arrest you for harboring

859
01:05:00,200 --> 01:05:01,201
escape prisoners of war.

860
01:05:06,859 --> 01:05:07,381
[speaking german]

861
01:05:30,796 --> 01:05:31,318
[speaking german]

862
01:05:57,214 --> 01:05:58,519
I've just seen the signal!

863
01:06:02,654 --> 01:06:04,134
We're at the frontier.

864
01:06:04,177 --> 01:06:05,613
There's danger.

865
01:06:05,657 --> 01:06:08,051
You'll have to swim
forth 100 yards upstream,

866
01:06:08,094 --> 01:06:08,834
and you'll be safe.

867
01:06:25,372 --> 01:06:26,112
You Madame Moulin.

868
01:06:26,156 --> 01:06:27,026
I am.

869
01:06:27,070 --> 01:06:29,028
You're under arrest.

870
01:06:29,072 --> 01:06:32,989
[speaking german]

871
01:06:33,032 --> 01:06:34,381
Get your hands off me!

872
01:07:17,946 --> 01:07:19,818
I don't like it, [inaudible].

873
01:07:19,861 --> 01:07:22,255
I don't like it.

874
01:07:22,299 --> 01:07:26,172
You can get no information
from the military authorities.

875
01:07:26,216 --> 01:07:28,957
I hear unofficially
trial is imminent.

876
01:07:39,011 --> 01:07:41,013
If you could establish
espionage it would be simple.

877
01:07:41,057 --> 01:07:42,232
Yeah.

878
01:07:42,275 --> 01:07:44,973
But we have no
[inaudible] evidence.

879
01:07:45,017 --> 01:07:47,802
But there is an alternative.

880
01:07:47,846 --> 01:07:51,197
We can charge her on a Section
58 of the military code which

881
01:07:51,241 --> 01:07:52,851
makes furnishing
the enemy with men,

882
01:07:52,894 --> 01:07:55,593
an offense punishable by death.

883
01:07:55,636 --> 01:08:00,467
Go yourself and see the lawyer
representing Miss Cavell.

884
01:08:00,511 --> 01:08:03,949
Tell him to impress upon the court

885
01:08:03,992 --> 01:08:08,214
that she is a woman who has
sacrificed her life in all

886
01:08:08,258 --> 01:08:12,436
this storm of hatred,
trying to create a refuge

887
01:08:12,479 --> 01:08:14,351
of goodwill and forgiveness.

888
01:08:14,394 --> 01:08:16,483
I will, sir.

889
01:08:16,527 --> 01:08:17,571
But you mustn't stress yourself.

890
01:08:20,922 --> 01:08:23,055
I will bring out all the
points made by your ministry

891
01:08:23,099 --> 01:08:25,275
in my speech for her defense.

892
01:08:25,318 --> 01:08:28,843
But your presence at the trial
would cause a great prejudice.

893
01:08:28,887 --> 01:08:30,758
The German judges would feel
that you were exercising

894
01:08:30,802 --> 01:08:32,108
a kind of supervision.

895
01:08:32,151 --> 01:08:33,935
Oh, I wouldn't have that happen.

896
01:08:33,979 --> 01:08:35,415
But you will keep us
well advised, won't you?

897
01:08:35,459 --> 01:08:37,635
Of course.

898
01:08:37,678 --> 01:08:39,854
I suppose at the worst it could
only be a term of imprisonment.

899
01:08:39,898 --> 01:08:42,118
That's the worst.

900
01:08:42,161 --> 01:08:43,423
Thank you.

901
01:08:43,467 --> 01:08:44,990
Of course, you are
the public prosecutor

902
01:08:45,033 --> 01:08:46,818
and I have no wish to
interfere with your conduct

903
01:08:46,861 --> 01:08:49,995
of the case, [inaudible].

904
01:08:50,038 --> 01:08:51,475
Certainly.

905
01:08:51,518 --> 01:08:53,738
There may be a [inaudible]
of checks [inaudible]...

906
01:08:53,781 --> 01:08:55,218
[inaudible]

907
01:08:55,261 --> 01:08:57,002
that the military code
applies only to Germans

908
01:08:57,045 --> 01:08:59,047
supplying the enemy with men.

909
01:08:59,091 --> 01:09:00,440
A law which is good
enough for Germans

910
01:09:00,484 --> 01:09:01,876
is good enough for these people.

911
01:09:33,952 --> 01:09:36,346
Of course, we would have been
to see you before, matron,

912
01:09:36,389 --> 01:09:38,391
if I'd been able to get a permit.

913
01:09:38,435 --> 01:09:39,914
Yes, I know.

914
01:09:39,958 --> 01:09:42,352
It seems more like seven
years than seven weeks

915
01:09:42,395 --> 01:09:43,831
since you left.

916
01:09:43,875 --> 01:09:45,746
It has been a long time.

917
01:09:45,790 --> 01:09:47,226
Everything has progressing quite

918
01:09:47,270 --> 01:09:49,228
satisfactorily with the home.

919
01:09:49,272 --> 01:09:50,708
Oh, yes, matron.

920
01:09:50,751 --> 01:09:53,319
We've been carrying on as
though you were with us.

921
01:09:53,363 --> 01:09:55,103
That's right.

922
01:09:55,147 --> 01:09:57,454
And you'll soon be back again
for the directors of Institute

923
01:09:57,497 --> 01:09:59,020
have arranged for an advoca...

924
01:09:59,064 --> 01:10:00,370
You're not permit to discuss
any matter in connection

925
01:10:00,413 --> 01:10:01,980
with the trial.

926
01:10:02,023 --> 01:10:04,069
Surely, I'm permitted to
tell Miss Cavell what...

927
01:10:04,112 --> 01:10:05,244
You will discuss nothing with her

928
01:10:05,288 --> 01:10:06,593
in connection with her case.

929
01:10:06,637 --> 01:10:08,291
That is the condition
of your [inaudible]

930
01:10:08,334 --> 01:10:09,814
under German military law.

931
01:10:09,857 --> 01:10:11,337
That may be all right for
Germans, but I'm an American

932
01:10:11,381 --> 01:10:12,512
and I think it's...

933
01:10:12,556 --> 01:10:13,731
I'm not interested what you think.

934
01:10:13,774 --> 01:10:15,211
They can't stop me from telling you

935
01:10:15,254 --> 01:10:16,603
an attorney has been
engaged for your defense.

936
01:10:16,647 --> 01:10:18,562
Mary, my dear, don't
distress yourself.

937
01:10:18,605 --> 01:10:20,433
It can do no good.

938
01:10:20,477 --> 01:10:21,913
It's all so unfair
to those of us who

939
01:10:21,956 --> 01:10:23,828
know how much good you've done.

940
01:10:26,874 --> 01:10:29,268
Oh, [inaudible].

941
01:10:29,312 --> 01:10:30,791
I know just how you feel.

942
01:10:30,835 --> 01:10:32,271
GERMAN GUARD [OFFSCREEN]:
Fraulein [inaudible].

943
01:10:32,315 --> 01:10:35,753
Sister, take her back
and let her rest a while.

944
01:10:35,796 --> 01:10:37,058
Yes, matron.

945
01:10:37,102 --> 01:10:38,146
We'll come and see you soon.

946
01:10:50,115 --> 01:10:55,686
That situation calls
for the severest penalty.

947
01:10:55,729 --> 01:10:58,645
Pity [inaudible].

948
01:10:58,689 --> 01:11:01,735
Leniency would only be
mistaken for a weakness.

949
01:11:01,779 --> 01:11:04,782
OFFICER [OFFSCREEN]: The
charge then is to be [inaudible]

950
01:11:04,825 --> 01:11:06,827
through the death penalty.

951
01:11:06,871 --> 01:11:08,220
I wish an example made.

952
01:11:11,223 --> 01:11:14,574
The network of conspiracy unravels,

953
01:11:14,618 --> 01:11:17,142
but it's still [inaudible].

954
01:11:17,185 --> 01:11:19,144
As far as purpose, the furnishing

955
01:11:19,187 --> 01:11:22,103
of soldiers to the enemy.

956
01:11:22,147 --> 01:11:24,845
Directed in Brussels
by this woman, Cavell,

957
01:11:24,889 --> 01:11:28,153
and her accomplices
who are here on trial.

958
01:11:28,196 --> 01:11:32,026
There has been steady traffic
to [inaudible] Germany,

959
01:11:32,070 --> 01:11:39,295
and [inaudible] enemies under
this woman, Cavell's direction.

960
01:11:39,338 --> 01:11:41,688
Men of military age have succeeded

961
01:11:41,732 --> 01:11:44,474
in passing the frontier.

962
01:11:44,517 --> 01:11:46,867
It remains to be seen
whether what has been charged

963
01:11:46,911 --> 01:11:50,523
against them constitutes
their [inaudible],

964
01:11:50,567 --> 01:11:53,831
or whether the true purpose
of this organization

965
01:11:53,874 --> 01:11:55,485
was that of espionage.

966
01:11:58,444 --> 01:12:00,751
[SARCASTICALLY] Espionage.

967
01:12:00,794 --> 01:12:02,187
[inaudible]

968
01:12:02,230 --> 01:12:03,536
Spying.

969
01:12:03,580 --> 01:12:05,930
Spying

970
01:12:05,973 --> 01:12:09,281
I wish to call the head of
our counter espionage, Captain

971
01:12:09,325 --> 01:12:10,717
Heinrichs.

972
01:12:10,761 --> 01:12:11,544
Captain Heinrichs.

973
01:12:15,983 --> 01:12:17,855
You know [inaudible] Miss Cavell?

974
01:12:17,898 --> 01:12:19,204
Yes.

975
01:12:19,247 --> 01:12:20,988
Will you produce a
statement taken by yourself?

976
01:12:21,032 --> 01:12:22,468
I do.

977
01:12:22,512 --> 01:12:24,688
The statement taken
correct in every detail.

978
01:12:24,731 --> 01:12:27,081
It was taken with every precaution.

979
01:12:27,125 --> 01:12:28,735
No possibility of error.

980
01:12:28,779 --> 01:12:32,609
Is it suggested that this
organization existed not only

981
01:12:32,652 --> 01:12:36,308
for the purpose of providing
the enemy with men,

982
01:12:36,352 --> 01:12:37,570
but also for espionage?

983
01:12:41,139 --> 01:12:42,575
I have no proof of
that, [inaudible].

984
01:12:46,536 --> 01:12:49,365
All of your witnesses
has been drawn from

985
01:12:49,408 --> 01:12:51,541
military intelligence service.

986
01:12:51,584 --> 01:12:55,371
Is there no independent
or civilian witnesses?

987
01:12:59,853 --> 01:13:01,681
[speaking german]

988
01:13:01,725 --> 01:13:04,815
[inaudible], I have one
important witness whose

989
01:13:04,858 --> 01:13:06,338
evidence alone should be sufficient

990
01:13:06,382 --> 01:13:09,036
to convict all the prisoners.

991
01:13:09,080 --> 01:13:11,038
I call Francois Rappard.

992
01:13:13,824 --> 01:13:14,694
Francois Rappard.

993
01:13:18,350 --> 01:13:19,220
Francois Rappard.

994
01:13:26,271 --> 01:13:27,446
Francois!

995
01:13:27,490 --> 01:13:28,142
Francois!

996
01:13:33,626 --> 01:13:37,151
Francois Rappard, do you
know the accused, Miss Cavell?

997
01:13:37,195 --> 01:13:39,153
Yes.

998
01:13:39,197 --> 01:13:41,591
Did you, at the request
of the woman Cavell,

999
01:13:41,634 --> 01:13:44,768
conduct fugitive soldiers
through [inaudible] border?

1000
01:13:44,811 --> 01:13:47,553
Yes.

1001
01:13:47,597 --> 01:13:49,207
Did you hear them
say that they were

1002
01:13:49,250 --> 01:13:51,296
going back to join the Army
and fight against Germany?

1003
01:13:54,517 --> 01:13:55,213
Francois Rappard!

1004
01:13:58,521 --> 01:14:00,523
Did you hear them say they were
going back to join the Army

1005
01:14:00,566 --> 01:14:01,611
and fight against Germany?

1006
01:14:04,701 --> 01:14:06,572
[scream] Don't
tell them, Francois!

1007
01:14:09,662 --> 01:14:13,144
[crying] [inaudible]

1008
01:14:13,187 --> 01:14:14,101
I know, [inaudible].

1009
01:14:14,145 --> 01:14:15,494
I know, dear.

1010
01:14:26,418 --> 01:14:28,289
We are doing
everything in our power.

1011
01:14:28,333 --> 01:14:31,902
Yes, we know, Mr. Gibson,
and we're very grateful.

1012
01:14:31,945 --> 01:14:34,034
But we can't understand
why they wouldn't allow

1013
01:14:34,078 --> 01:14:35,775
you to be present at the trial.

1014
01:14:35,819 --> 01:14:38,343
Her defending counsel said it
would prejudice her if I did.

1015
01:14:38,386 --> 01:14:41,085
But he assured me she would
receive a perfectly fair trial,

1016
01:14:41,128 --> 01:14:43,000
and that he would do
his utmost independent

1017
01:14:43,043 --> 01:14:44,654
and the best of his ability.

1018
01:14:44,697 --> 01:14:47,526
Let the court put itself in
the position of this woman.

1019
01:14:47,570 --> 01:14:50,007
Dedicated as she had
been throughout her life

1020
01:14:50,050 --> 01:14:52,052
to the service of the helpless.

1021
01:14:52,096 --> 01:14:54,794
And ask themselves what they
would have done in the face

1022
01:14:54,838 --> 01:14:58,972
of the irresistible impulse to
assist those unhappy fugitives

1023
01:14:59,016 --> 01:15:00,452
whom she had hidden in her house,

1024
01:15:00,496 --> 01:15:02,976
or given assistance from her purse.

1025
01:15:03,020 --> 01:15:05,544
Her only motive in
acting as she has done

1026
01:15:05,588 --> 01:15:08,504
was to save men whom she
thought to be in danger

1027
01:15:08,547 --> 01:15:10,375
and help them escape
from the country.

1028
01:15:10,418 --> 01:15:13,247
She never for a moment
had it in her mind

1029
01:15:13,291 --> 01:15:15,859
to do an injury to Germany.

1030
01:15:15,902 --> 01:15:21,429
The law of Miss Cavell is
far above any military code.

1031
01:15:21,473 --> 01:15:25,608
A law infinitely higher than
war and the idea of [inaudible].

1032
01:15:30,613 --> 01:15:36,096
The life of that woman belongs
to the sick and wounded.

1033
01:15:36,140 --> 01:15:39,360
The lives that many Germans
soldiers owe to her skill

1034
01:15:39,404 --> 01:15:41,798
in the early days of the war dries

1035
01:15:41,841 --> 01:15:44,104
out against the
shedding of her blood

1036
01:15:44,148 --> 01:15:46,803
by the German authorities.

1037
01:15:46,846 --> 01:15:51,416
If what she has done is
deserving of punishment,

1038
01:15:51,459 --> 01:15:54,071
then detention for the
duration of the war

1039
01:15:54,114 --> 01:15:56,682
is the maximum penalty
that should be inflicted.

1040
01:16:00,860 --> 01:16:02,688
Could it be doubted
that this organization

1041
01:16:02,732 --> 01:16:04,690
was a premeditated
conspiracy to undermine

1042
01:16:04,734 --> 01:16:06,387
the German authorities?

1043
01:16:06,431 --> 01:16:09,956
Was it not plain from the fact
that the enemy was benefited

1044
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:12,480
and Germany injured
by their action?

1045
01:16:12,524 --> 01:16:15,483
By their breach of law, these
people put in danger the lives,

1046
01:16:15,527 --> 01:16:18,399
and probably cause for
death of brave German

1047
01:16:18,443 --> 01:16:22,055
soldiers in the front line.

1048
01:16:22,099 --> 01:16:23,622
The head of this organization was

1049
01:16:23,666 --> 01:16:27,147
undoubtedly the woman Cavell.

1050
01:16:27,191 --> 01:16:30,368
It will be said that
she was a nurse.

1051
01:16:30,411 --> 01:16:33,458
A nurse has obligations
beyond military code.

1052
01:16:33,501 --> 01:16:36,809
To make use of her calling
as a cloak for recruiting

1053
01:16:36,853 --> 01:16:39,246
soldiers to the enemy
was a gross abuse

1054
01:16:39,290 --> 01:16:41,205
of her noble profession.

1055
01:16:41,248 --> 01:16:45,688
[german]

1056
01:16:45,731 --> 01:16:47,124
Miss Cavell, please.

1057
01:17:02,879 --> 01:17:06,056
Do you wish to say
anything further to what

1058
01:17:06,099 --> 01:17:08,841
has been said on your behalf?

1059
01:17:08,885 --> 01:17:12,105
I have nothing further to say.

1060
01:17:12,149 --> 01:17:17,371
You admit having assisted
soldiers to cross the frontier?

1061
01:17:17,415 --> 01:17:19,112
I do.

1062
01:17:19,156 --> 01:17:22,289
How many of these men did you
assist in leaving the country?

1063
01:17:22,333 --> 01:17:24,683
About 200.

1064
01:17:24,727 --> 01:17:29,819
Did you know the offense
is punishable with death?

1065
01:17:29,862 --> 01:17:30,558
I did.

1066
01:17:37,348 --> 01:17:42,745
Against the woman Cavell, I
demand the penalty of death.

1067
01:17:42,788 --> 01:17:46,618
[music playing]

1068
01:17:52,537 --> 01:17:55,932
The case against the
woman Cavell is closed.

1069
01:17:55,975 --> 01:17:58,891
Sentence will be discussed
and put to the vote.

1070
01:17:58,935 --> 01:18:01,720
[music playing]

1071
01:18:14,254 --> 01:18:14,951
[inaudible].

1072
01:18:18,519 --> 01:18:20,739
Please do not be afraid.

1073
01:18:20,783 --> 01:18:23,046
He demands the extreme
penalty, but they

1074
01:18:23,089 --> 01:18:25,222
would never carry it out.

1075
01:18:25,265 --> 01:18:26,005
Thank you.

1076
01:18:26,049 --> 01:18:26,876
You are very kind.

1077
01:18:30,967 --> 01:18:33,796
[bell ring]

1078
01:18:36,581 --> 01:18:37,277
[inaudible]

1079
01:18:44,807 --> 01:18:47,331
I think we all seem sentimental
because she's a woman.

1080
01:18:47,374 --> 01:18:48,506
Precisely.

1081
01:18:48,549 --> 01:18:49,681
Is there any thought in your mind

1082
01:18:49,725 --> 01:18:51,291
this woman was the leading spirit?

1083
01:18:51,335 --> 01:18:52,466
None whatever.

1084
01:18:52,510 --> 01:18:54,164
Then there is no more to be said.

1085
01:18:54,207 --> 01:18:55,295
I confirm the sentence.

1086
01:18:55,339 --> 01:18:56,949
[inaudible]

1087
01:18:56,993 --> 01:18:59,256
Have an order drawn
up for my signature,

1088
01:18:59,299 --> 01:19:03,695
directing it to be carried
out as early as possible.

1089
01:19:03,739 --> 01:19:07,612
Gentlemen, good day.

1090
01:19:24,237 --> 01:19:32,115
[inaudible] Thank you.

1091
01:19:47,173 --> 01:19:49,654
My dear nurses.

1092
01:19:49,697 --> 01:19:52,918
Your charming letter
gave me great pleasure,

1093
01:19:52,962 --> 01:19:56,704
and your lovely flowers
have made my cell gay.

1094
01:19:56,748 --> 01:20:00,099
The roses are still fresh.

1095
01:20:00,143 --> 01:20:03,929
But the chrysanthemums did not
like prison any more than I do.

1096
01:20:03,973 --> 01:20:08,455
Hence, they did not live very long.

1097
01:20:08,499 --> 01:20:10,718
If you were in my
place you would realize

1098
01:20:10,762 --> 01:20:13,983
how precious liberty is.

1099
01:20:14,026 --> 01:20:17,943
But I hope by the time
this letter reaches you,

1100
01:20:17,987 --> 01:20:20,337
you will have better
news [inaudible].

1101
01:20:28,345 --> 01:20:28,867
[speaking german]

1102
01:20:41,706 --> 01:20:44,927
Fraulein Cavell, I
have to read to you

1103
01:20:44,970 --> 01:20:45,928
the sentence of the court.

1104
01:20:50,889 --> 01:20:53,370
Judgment given this day by
military tribunal of the Courts

1105
01:20:53,413 --> 01:20:56,634
of Justice Brussels against
Edith Cavell, directors

1106
01:20:56,677 --> 01:20:59,767
of the Berkendael Medical
Institute for treason

1107
01:20:59,811 --> 01:21:00,812
commit in time of war.

1108
01:21:05,208 --> 01:21:08,994
Sentence, death.

1109
01:21:09,038 --> 01:21:10,300
We carry it out at dawn.

1110
01:21:18,090 --> 01:21:18,874
Is there anything you wish?

1111
01:21:22,312 --> 01:21:26,055
I would like to see
an English chaplain.

1112
01:21:26,098 --> 01:21:27,317
[inaudible], Fraulein.

1113
01:21:30,581 --> 01:21:31,103
[speaking german]

1114
01:22:14,842 --> 01:22:15,495
I [inaudible].

1115
01:22:22,198 --> 01:22:25,853
Gentlemen, what can I do for you?

1116
01:22:25,897 --> 01:22:27,986
Will you inform,
Mr. Excellency,

1117
01:22:28,030 --> 01:22:31,511
if the sentence in the Cavell
affair has been promulgated?

1118
01:22:31,555 --> 01:22:33,383
Any information that
you are entitled to

1119
01:22:33,426 --> 01:22:36,516
will reach you at the
proper time, Mr. Gibson.

1120
01:22:36,560 --> 01:22:38,475
I... I understand that.

1121
01:22:38,518 --> 01:22:40,477
But would you tell me
if the court has passed

1122
01:22:40,520 --> 01:22:42,087
sentence on the prisoner.

1123
01:22:42,131 --> 01:22:45,090
The court has not yet
published its findings.

1124
01:22:45,134 --> 01:22:47,963
Then I presume no sentence
would be carried out

1125
01:22:48,006 --> 01:22:49,877
until it has been made public.

1126
01:22:49,921 --> 01:22:51,531
The sentence will be carried out

1127
01:22:51,575 --> 01:22:53,707
when the legal requirements
of the Imperial [inaudible]

1128
01:22:53,751 --> 01:22:55,013
has been fulfilled.

1129
01:22:55,057 --> 01:22:56,623
Good day, Mr. Gibson.

1130
01:22:56,667 --> 01:22:57,363
Good day, [inaudible].

1131
01:23:01,150 --> 01:23:08,505
[playing music]

1132
01:23:08,548 --> 01:23:10,115
[speaking german]

1133
01:23:10,159 --> 01:23:11,899
Firing squad, you'll meet
5 o'clock tomorrow morning.

1134
01:23:11,943 --> 01:23:12,813
- Kirk?
- Ya.

1135
01:23:12,857 --> 01:23:13,727
- [inaudible]
- Ya.

1136
01:23:13,771 --> 01:23:14,946
Rammler?

1137
01:23:14,990 --> 01:23:17,557
May I have leave
of parade, Sergeant?

1138
01:23:17,601 --> 01:23:20,430
I wish to report sick.

1139
01:23:20,473 --> 01:23:23,433
Yellow fever, Private Rammler?

1140
01:23:23,476 --> 01:23:26,914
I am... I am sick.

1141
01:23:26,958 --> 01:23:29,352
There's an ugly word for
this complaint of yours.

1142
01:23:29,395 --> 01:23:33,051
I don't mind fighting,
but this is murder.

1143
01:23:33,095 --> 01:23:35,706
You refuse to be ordered?

1144
01:23:35,749 --> 01:23:37,186
I do.

1145
01:23:37,229 --> 01:23:38,709
Private Rammler, you are
arrest for insubordination.

1146
01:23:38,752 --> 01:23:39,405
[speaking german]

1147
01:23:45,411 --> 01:23:49,241
[music playing]

1148
01:23:58,772 --> 01:23:59,686
Would you please be seated.

1149
01:23:59,730 --> 01:24:00,861
I have called Mr. Gibson.

1150
01:24:10,871 --> 01:24:12,525
This note has just
come for you, sir.

1151
01:24:12,569 --> 01:24:13,918
It's very urgent.

1152
01:24:13,961 --> 01:24:15,615
Oh, thanks.

1153
01:24:15,659 --> 01:24:18,792
Oh, Sister Watkins has just
called to see you, Mr. Gibson.

1154
01:24:18,836 --> 01:24:19,880
Better go and see her.

1155
01:24:19,924 --> 01:24:20,794
She may have news.

1156
01:24:28,193 --> 01:24:30,761
Mr. Gibson, Miss Cavell
has been sentenced to death.

1157
01:24:30,804 --> 01:24:31,805
What?

1158
01:24:31,849 --> 01:24:33,024
Yes, and it's tomorrow morning.

1159
01:24:33,068 --> 01:24:33,981
It can't be possible!

1160
01:24:34,025 --> 01:24:35,461
I assure you it is so.

1161
01:24:35,505 --> 01:24:36,897
We were told by the deputy
governor, Mr. Gibson.

1162
01:24:36,941 --> 01:24:38,247
Excuse me, sir.

1163
01:24:38,290 --> 01:24:39,683
Mr. Whitlock wishes to
see you immediately.

1164
01:24:39,726 --> 01:24:40,727
Wait here, I'll be right back.

1165
01:24:46,733 --> 01:24:48,344
[inaudible] we're being fooled.

1166
01:24:48,387 --> 01:24:49,084
Read that.

1167
01:24:54,524 --> 01:24:56,308
This confirms what
Sister Watkins told me.

1168
01:24:56,352 --> 01:24:57,527
I want to write a note.

1169
01:25:02,619 --> 01:25:05,100
They're going to kill her, sister.

1170
01:25:05,143 --> 01:25:06,579
I know it.

1171
01:25:06,623 --> 01:25:09,060
They can't.

1172
01:25:09,104 --> 01:25:09,974
They couldn't.

1173
01:25:15,110 --> 01:25:17,329
If only I weren't tied to this bed!

1174
01:25:17,373 --> 01:25:18,939
Couldn't have caught
it at a worse time, sir.

1175
01:25:18,983 --> 01:25:20,202
Get that to [inaudible].

1176
01:25:20,245 --> 01:25:21,594
See that he reads it himself.

1177
01:25:21,638 --> 01:25:22,378
Very well, sir.

1178
01:25:37,306 --> 01:25:40,047
If you will forgive
me, I'm a little dazed.

1179
01:25:40,091 --> 01:25:43,442
I'm distressed to meet you
under these circumstances.

1180
01:25:43,486 --> 01:25:47,403
If there is anything
I can do to help.

1181
01:25:47,446 --> 01:25:50,362
So much to do before
my work was finished.

1182
01:25:50,406 --> 01:25:53,365
[inaudible] Institute,
the [inaudible].

1183
01:25:53,409 --> 01:25:54,758
It is God's will.

1184
01:25:57,891 --> 01:25:59,806
God's will.

1185
01:25:59,850 --> 01:26:04,463
Sometimes so difficult
to comprehend.

1186
01:26:04,507 --> 01:26:08,946
That is what my mother
would say if she were here.

1187
01:26:08,989 --> 01:26:10,904
Will you see that a
message reaches her?

1188
01:26:10,948 --> 01:26:13,385
Tell her that I am
quite happy, that I have

1189
01:26:13,429 --> 01:26:17,302
no regret for what I have done.

1190
01:26:17,346 --> 01:26:18,173
Oh, Gibson.

1191
01:26:18,216 --> 01:26:19,217
[inaudible]

1192
01:26:19,261 --> 01:26:20,827
Your Excellency, I have the honor

1193
01:26:20,871 --> 01:26:22,002
to bring you a personal note.

1194
01:26:22,046 --> 01:26:23,526
[inaudible] from my minister.

1195
01:26:41,979 --> 01:26:43,894
I can do nothing in this matter.

1196
01:26:43,937 --> 01:26:45,504
But surely, your Excellency, you

1197
01:26:45,548 --> 01:26:46,984
don't wish me to
understand that you intend

1198
01:26:47,027 --> 01:26:48,464
the sentence to be carried out.

1199
01:26:48,507 --> 01:26:50,640
I have no say in the
matter, Mr. Gibson.

1200
01:26:50,683 --> 01:26:52,772
Decision rests with the military
government, [inaudible].

1201
01:26:52,816 --> 01:26:53,947
But your Excellency...

1202
01:26:53,991 --> 01:26:55,558
The military governor of Brussels

1203
01:26:55,601 --> 01:26:57,908
is the confirming authority,
and no one can interfere.

1204
01:26:57,951 --> 01:26:59,170
I know, but couldn't...

1205
01:26:59,214 --> 01:27:01,477
I doubt if the Kaiser
himself could do so.

1206
01:27:01,520 --> 01:27:03,827
You mean this woman is in
the grip of your war machine?

1207
01:27:03,870 --> 01:27:06,264
I mean nothing, Mr. Gibson.

1208
01:27:06,308 --> 01:27:08,048
When is the sentence
to be carried out?

1209
01:27:08,092 --> 01:27:10,225
I have not been informed.

1210
01:27:10,268 --> 01:27:10,921
Governor.

1211
01:27:17,319 --> 01:27:19,016
They've treated you considerately

1212
01:27:19,059 --> 01:27:20,452
whilst you've been here?

1213
01:27:20,496 --> 01:27:23,455
Oh yes, they've all been very kind.

1214
01:27:23,499 --> 01:27:27,938
But thank God for these few
quiet weeks before the end.

1215
01:27:27,981 --> 01:27:30,941
Life has always been hurried
and full of difficulties.

1216
01:27:30,984 --> 01:27:33,291
This time of rest has
been a great mercy.

1217
01:27:41,952 --> 01:27:44,171
[inaudible], Mr. Gibson's
here to see Excellence.

1218
01:27:44,215 --> 01:27:44,998
He's out.

1219
01:27:48,480 --> 01:27:50,047
His Excellence is out, Herr Gibson.

1220
01:27:50,090 --> 01:27:51,091
I wish to see him.

1221
01:27:51,135 --> 01:27:51,962
I'm afraid that's not possible.

1222
01:27:52,005 --> 01:27:53,485
But this is most urgent.

1223
01:27:53,529 --> 01:27:55,400
I have a message for him
from the American minister.

1224
01:27:55,444 --> 01:27:57,315
I'll see he gets it first
thing in the morning.

1225
01:27:57,359 --> 01:27:59,230
You know perfectly
well, Captain Heinrichs,

1226
01:27:59,274 --> 01:28:01,798
that would be too late.

1227
01:28:01,841 --> 01:28:03,887
As the Governor's had a
very trying day, Herr Gibson.

1228
01:28:03,930 --> 01:28:05,149
I dare not take the responsibility

1229
01:28:05,192 --> 01:28:06,498
of disturbing him.

1230
01:28:06,542 --> 01:28:07,760
Oh, don't worry about
the responsibility.

1231
01:28:07,804 --> 01:28:09,458
The American minister
would take that.

1232
01:28:09,501 --> 01:28:11,068
Unfortunately, Herr Gibson,
this is military headquarters,

1233
01:28:11,111 --> 01:28:12,330
not the American embassy.

1234
01:28:12,374 --> 01:28:13,113
I have my orders.

1235
01:28:13,157 --> 01:28:13,853
Why this is...

1236
01:28:18,423 --> 01:28:22,819
Mr. Gibson, at the opera.

1237
01:28:22,862 --> 01:28:24,299
Thank you.

1238
01:28:24,342 --> 01:28:27,563
[music playing]

1239
01:28:33,046 --> 01:28:35,310
Please, I'll tell him
at the end of this act.

1240
01:28:35,353 --> 01:28:36,746
But this is my [inaudible].

1241
01:28:36,789 --> 01:28:37,703
I must see him immediately.

1242
01:28:41,316 --> 01:28:42,795
This is the general's
own private box.

1243
01:28:42,839 --> 01:28:44,144
You cannot go in.

1244
01:28:44,188 --> 01:28:45,363
I wish to see General Von Ehrhardt.

1245
01:28:45,407 --> 01:28:46,712
He cannot be disturbed.

1246
01:28:46,756 --> 01:28:47,757
My name is Gibson.

1247
01:28:47,800 --> 01:28:49,193
I'm from the American Embassy.

1248
01:28:49,236 --> 01:28:50,586
Please tell him I'm here.

1249
01:29:07,167 --> 01:29:07,994
Mr. Gibson, [inaudible].

1250
01:29:08,038 --> 01:29:09,779
Most irregular I know.

1251
01:29:09,822 --> 01:29:11,737
But my minister will
take the responsibility.

1252
01:29:11,781 --> 01:29:13,478
What is your business?

1253
01:29:13,522 --> 01:29:16,873
General, there is a rumor or I
have been told that Miss Cavell

1254
01:29:16,916 --> 01:29:17,917
has been sentenced to death.

1255
01:29:17,961 --> 01:29:19,528
Yes, sir.

1256
01:29:19,571 --> 01:29:21,094
Moreover, the sentence is to
be carried out in the morning.

1257
01:29:21,138 --> 01:29:22,531
At dawn.

1258
01:29:22,574 --> 01:29:23,793
[gasp].

1259
01:29:23,836 --> 01:29:25,229
Well, don't you
realize what it means

1260
01:29:25,272 --> 01:29:26,926
if you execute this woman?

1261
01:29:26,970 --> 01:29:29,364
German will be banded
throughout the civilized world.

1262
01:29:29,407 --> 01:29:31,104
Don't you realize what a
terrible disservice you

1263
01:29:31,148 --> 01:29:32,584
are doing your own [inaudible]?

1264
01:29:32,628 --> 01:29:35,108
To fail in my duty would
be a far worse disservice.

1265
01:29:35,152 --> 01:29:37,023
The maintenance of
good order in Brussels

1266
01:29:37,067 --> 01:29:38,895
requires these penalties
be carried out.

1267
01:29:38,938 --> 01:29:40,157
The maintenance of
order could never

1268
01:29:40,200 --> 01:29:41,637
require the murder of a woman.

1269
01:29:41,680 --> 01:29:44,901
Your language is hardly
diplomatic, Mr. Gibson.

1270
01:29:44,944 --> 01:29:47,207
Moreover, it is most inexact.

1271
01:29:47,251 --> 01:29:49,340
One doesn't apply the term
murder to the execution

1272
01:29:49,384 --> 01:29:50,689
of those who have
been very convicted

1273
01:29:50,733 --> 01:29:53,649
on their own admissions
of capital offenses.

1274
01:29:53,692 --> 01:29:56,129
Tried before a secret tribunal.

1275
01:29:56,173 --> 01:29:57,957
Denied all communication
with her legal advisor.

1276
01:29:58,001 --> 01:29:59,611
Is that your [inaudible]...

1277
01:29:59,655 --> 01:30:01,352
I have no wish to discuss the
procedure of our German courts

1278
01:30:01,396 --> 01:30:02,701
[inaudible].

1279
01:30:02,745 --> 01:30:04,486
If that is all you have
to say, Mr. Gibson.

1280
01:30:04,529 --> 01:30:06,749
I have much to say.

1281
01:30:06,792 --> 01:30:10,405
A sense of horror so
strong, your Excellency

1282
01:30:10,448 --> 01:30:12,276
will make allowance.

1283
01:30:12,319 --> 01:30:16,367
This affair, it all seemed
so simple and logical to you.

1284
01:30:16,411 --> 01:30:18,587
[inaudible] and tragedy.

1285
01:30:18,630 --> 01:30:20,676
A crime against humanity.

1286
01:30:20,719 --> 01:30:22,634
You regard is a
crime against humanity

1287
01:30:22,678 --> 01:30:24,854
the punishment of people
for a military offenses

1288
01:30:24,897 --> 01:30:26,072
in time of war?

1289
01:30:26,116 --> 01:30:27,639
Yes, but your Excellency, a woman?

1290
01:30:27,683 --> 01:30:29,032
[inaudible] mixed up in
these affairs, Mr. Gibson.

1291
01:30:29,075 --> 01:30:30,947
Very well, then imprison her.

1292
01:30:30,990 --> 01:30:33,819
Put her out of the way
until the war's over.

1293
01:30:33,863 --> 01:30:37,083
No recommendation
to mercy was made.

1294
01:30:37,127 --> 01:30:39,521
The court has decided to
punish her with death.

1295
01:30:42,567 --> 01:30:48,443
Who knows thy cross before
my closing eyes shine

1296
01:30:48,486 --> 01:30:53,317
through the gloom and point
me to the skies, heaven

1297
01:30:53,360 --> 01:30:57,234
and morning grace, and
earth's [inaudible] shadows

1298
01:30:57,277 --> 01:31:03,066
flee in thy, in death
alone abide with me.

1299
01:31:03,109 --> 01:31:03,762
Amen.

1300
01:32:02,342 --> 01:32:04,606
[marching]

1301
01:32:13,832 --> 01:32:14,529
[speaking german].

1302
01:34:09,731 --> 01:34:14,083
EDITH CAVELL [VOICEOVER]: I
have no fear nor shrinking.

1303
01:34:14,126 --> 01:34:17,695
I have seen death so often.

1304
01:34:17,739 --> 01:34:22,308
It is no longer strange
or fearful to me.

1305
01:34:22,352 --> 01:34:23,092
[speaking german].

1306
01:34:23,135 --> 01:34:25,398
[music playing]

1307
01:34:34,843 --> 01:34:37,410
[singing]

1308
01:35:30,594 --> 01:35:36,818
Standing, as I do, before
God and eternity, I realize

1309
01:35:36,861 --> 01:35:40,430
that patriotism is not enough.

1310
01:35:40,473 --> 01:35:45,522
I must have no hatred or
bitterness towards anyone.

1311
01:35:45,565 --> 01:35:48,786
[music playing]
